# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting generally follows three steps: pre-bioprinting, bioprinting, and post-bioprinting.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Pre-bioprinting is the process of creating a model that the printer will later create and choosing the materials that will be used.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] One of the first steps is to obtain a biopsy of the organ, to sample cells.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Common technologies used for bioprinting are computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] To print with a layer-by-layer approach, tomographic reconstruction is done on the images.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The now-2D images are then sent to the printer to be made.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Once the image is created, certain cells are isolated and multiplied.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] These cells are then mixed with a special liquefied material that provides oxygen and other nutrients to keep them alive.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This aggregation of cells does not require a scaffold, and is required for placing in the tubular-like tissue fusion for processes such as extrusion.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In the second step, the liquid mixtures of cells, matrix, and nutrients known as bioinks are placed in a printer cartridge and deposited using the patients' medical scans.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] When a bioprinted pre-tissue is transferred to an incubator, this cell-based pre-tissue matures into a tissue.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting for fabricating biological constructs typically involves dispensing cells onto a biocompatible scaffold using a successive layer-by-layer approach to generate tissue-like three-dimensional structures.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Artificial organs such as livers and kidneys made by 3D bioprinting have been shown to lack crucial elements that affect the body such as working blood vessels, tubules for collecting urine, and the growth of billions of cells required for these organs.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Without these components the body has no way to get the essential nutrients and oxygen deep within their interiors.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Given that every tissue in the body is naturally composed of different cell types, many technologies for printing these cells vary in their ability to ensure stability and viability of the cells during the manufacturing process.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Some of the methods that are used for 3D bioprinting of cells are photolithography, magnetic 3D bioprinting, stereolithography, and direct cell extrusion.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The post-bioprinting process is necessary to create a stable structure from the biological material.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] If this process is not well-maintained, the mechanical integrity and function of the 3D printed object is at risk.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] To maintain the object, both mechanical and chemical stimulations are needed.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] These stimulations send signals to the cells to control the remodeling and growth of tissues.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In addition, in recent development, bioreactor technologies have allowed the rapid maturation of tissues, vascularization of tissues and the ability to survive transplants.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Bioreactors work in either providing convective nutrient transport, creating microgravity environments, changing the pressure causing solution to flow through the cells, or adding compression for dynamic or static loading.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Each type of bioreactor is ideal for different types of tissue, for example compression bioreactors are ideal for cartilage tissue.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Researchers in the field have developed approaches to produce living organs that are constructed with the appropriate biological and mechanical properties.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting is based on three main approaches: biomimicry, autonomous self-assembly and mini-tissue building blocks.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The first approach of bioprinting is called biomimicry.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The main goal of this approach is to create fabricated structures that are identical to the natural structure that are found in the tissues and organs in the human body.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Biomimicry requires duplication of the shape, framework, and the microenvironment of the organs and tissues.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The application of biomimicry in bioprinting involves creating both identical cellular and extracellular parts of organs.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] For this approach to be successful, the tissues must be replicated on a micro scale.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Therefore, it is necessary to understand the microenvironment, the nature of the biological forces in this microenvironment, the precise organization of functional and supporting cell types, solubility factors, and the composition of extracellular matrix.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The second approach of bioprinting is autonomous self-assembly.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This approach relies on the physical process of embryonic organ development as a model to replicate the tissues of interest.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] When cells are in their early development, they create their own extracellular matrix building block, the proper cell signaling, and independent arrangement and patterning to provide the required biological functions and micro-architecture.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly demands specific information about the developmental techniques of the tissues and organs of the embryo.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] There is a "scaffold-free" model that uses self-assembling spheroids that subjects to fusion and cell arrangement to resemble evolving tissues.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Autonomous self-assembly depends on the cell as the fundamental driver of histogenesis, guiding the building blocks, structural and functional properties of these tissues.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] It demands a deeper understanding of how embryonic tissues mechanisms develop as well as the microenvironment surrounded to create the bioprinted tissues.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The third approach of bioprinting is a combination of both the biomimicry and self-assembly approaches, called mini tissues.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Organs and tissues are built from very small functional components.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The mini-tissue approach takes these small pieces and arrange them into larger framework.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Akin to ordinary ink printers, bioprinters have three major components to them.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] These are the hardware used, the type of bio-ink, and the material it is printed on (biomaterials).
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Bio-ink is a material made from living cells that behaves much like a liquid, allowing people to 'print' it in order to create the desired shape.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] To make bio-ink, scientists create a slurry of cells that can be loaded into a cartridge and inserted into a specially designed printer, along with another cartridge containing a gel known as bio-paper.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In bioprinting, there are three major types of printers that have been used.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] These are inkjet, laser-assisted, and extrusion printers.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Inkjet printers are mainly used in bioprinting for fast and large-scale products.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] One type of inkjet printer, called drop-on-demand inkjet printer, prints materials in exact amounts, minimizing cost and waste.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Printers that use lasers provide high-resolution printing; however, these printers are often expensive.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion printers print cells layer-by-layer, just like 3D printing to create 3D constructs.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In addition to just cells, extrusion printers may also use hydrogels infused with cells.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Extrusion-based printing is a very common technique within the field of 3D printing which entails extruding, or forcing, a continuous stream of melted solid material or viscous liquid through a sort of orifice, often a nozzle or syringe.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] When it comes to extrusion based bioprinting, there are four main types of extrusion.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] These are pneumatic driven, piston driven, screw driven and eccentric screw driven (also known as progressing cavity pump).
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Each extrusion method has their own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Pneumatic extrusion uses pressurized air to force liquid bioink through a depositing agent.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Air filters are commonly used to sterilize the air before it is used, to ensure air pushing the bioink is not contaminated.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Piston driven extrusion uses a piston connected to a guide screw.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The linear motion of the piston squeezes material out of the nozzle.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven extrusion uses an auger screw to extrude material using rotational motion.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Screw driven devices allow for the use of higher viscosity materials and provide more volumetric control.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Eccentric screw driven systems allow for a much more precise deposition of low to high viscosity materials due to the self-sealing chambers in the extruder.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Once printed, many materials require a crosslinking step to achieve the desired mechanical properties for the construct, which can be achieved for example with the treatment of chemical agents or photo-crosslinkers.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Direct extrusion is one of the most common extrusion-based bioprinting techniques, wherein the pressurized force directs the bioink to flow out of the nozzle, and directly print the scaffold without any necessary casting.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The bioink itself for this approach can be a blend of polymer hydrogels, naturally derived materials such as collagen, and live cells suspended in the solution.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In this manner, scaffolds can be cultured post-print and without the need for further treatment for cellular seeding.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Some focus in the use of direct printing techniques is based upon the use of coaxial nozzle assemblies, or coaxial extrusion.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The coaxial nozzle setup enables the simultaneous extrusion of multiple material bioinks, capable of making multi-layered scaffolds in a single extrusion step.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The development of tubular structures has found the layered extrusion achieved via these techniques desirable for the radial variability in material characterization that it can offer, as the coaxial nozzle provides an inner and outer tube for bioink flow.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Indirect extrusion techniques for bioprinting rather require the printing of a base material of cell-laden hydrogels, but unlike direct extrusion contains a sacrificial hydrogel that can be trivially removed post-printing through thermal or chemical extraction.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The remaining resin solidifies and becomes the desired 3D-printed construct.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Laser-based bioprinting can be split into two major classes: those based on cell transfer technologies or photo-polymerization.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In cell transfer laser printing, a laser stimulates the connection between energy-absorbing material (e.g. gold, titanium, etc.) and the bioink.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This 'donor layer' vaporizes under the laser's irradiation, forming a bubble from the bioink layer which gets deposited from a jet.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Photo-polymerization techniques rather use photoinitiated reactions to solidify the ink, moving the beam path of a laser to induce the formation of a desired construct.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Certain laser frequencies paired with photopolymerization reactions can be carried out without damaging cells in the material.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In this form of printing, plastic residues are melted down and individual layered in sections to create a desired shape.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Nylon and PVA are examples of biomaterials used in this method.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This technique is most often used to design prototypes for prosthetics and cartilage construction.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Another form of bioprinting involves an inkjet printer, which is primarily used in biomedical settings.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This method prints detailed proteins and nucleic acids.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels are commonly selected as the bioink.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Cells can be printed on to a selected surface media to proliferate and ultimately differentiate.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] A drawback of this printing method is the ability of the bioinks such as hydrogels to clog the printing nozzle, due to their high viscosity.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Ideal inkjet bioprinting involves using a low polymer viscosity (ideally below 10 centipoise), low cell density (<10 million cells/mL), and low structural heights (<10 million cells/mL).
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] There are several other bioprinting techniques which are less commonly used.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Droplet-based bioprinting is a technique in which the bioink blend of cells and/or hydrogels are placed in droplets in precise positions.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Most common amongst this approach are thermal and piezoelectric-drop-on-demand techniques.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This method of bioprinting is often used experimentally with lung and ovarian cancer models.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Thermal technologies use short duration signals to heat the bioink, inducing the formation of small bubbles which are ejected.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Piezoelectric bioprinting has short duration current applied to a piezoelectric actuator, which induces a mechanical vibration capable of ejecting a small globule of bioink through the nozzle.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] A significant aspect of the study of droplet-based approaches to bioprinting is accounting for mechanical and thermal stress cells within the bioink experience near the nozzle-tip as they are extruded.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Bioinks are essential components of the bioprinting process.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] They are composed of living cells and enzymatic supplements to nurture an environment that supports the biological needs of the printed tissue.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The environment created by the bioink allows for the cell to attach, grow, and differentiate into its adult form.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Cell-encapsualting hydrogels are used in extrusion based bioprinting methods, while gelatin MethacryloylGelatin methacrylon (GelMA) and acellular comprised bioinks are most often used in tissue engineering techniques that require cross-linkage and precise structural integrity.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] It is essential for bioinks to help replicate the external cellular matrix environment that the cell would naturally occur in.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting can be used to reconstruct tissue from various regions of the body.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The precursor to the adoption of 3D printing in healthcare was a series of trials conducted by researchers at Boston Children's Hospital.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The team built replacement urinary bladders by hand for seven patients by constructing scaffolds, then layering the scaffolds with cells from the patients and allowing them to grow.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The trials were a success as the patients remained in good health 7 years after implantation, which led a research fellow named Anthony Atala, MD, to search for ways to automate the process.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Patients with end-stage bladder disease can now be treated by using bio-engineered bladder tissues to rebuild the damaged organ.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This technology can also potentially be applied to bone, skin, cartilage and muscle tissue.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Though one long-term goal of 3D bioprinting technology is to reconstruct an entire organ as well as minimize the problem of the lack of organs for transplantation.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] There has been little success in bioprinting of fully functional organs e.g. liver, skin, meniscus or pancreas.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Unlike implantable stents, organs have complex shapes and are significantly harder to bioprint.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] A bioprinted heart, for example, must not only meet structural requirements, but also vascularization, mechanical load, and electrical signal propagation requirements.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In 2022, the first success of a clinical trial for a 3D bioprinted transplant that is made from the patient's own cells, an external ear to treat microtia, was reported.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The limitations of 3D bioprinting are associated with physiologically irrelevant morphology and unsuccessful histological evaluation methods.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting contributes to significant advances in the medical field of tissue engineering by allowing for research to be done on innovative materials called biomaterials.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Some of the most notable bioengineered substances are usually stronger than the average bodily materials, including soft tissue and bone.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] These constituents can act as future substitutes, even improvements, for the original body materials.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In addition, the Defense Threat Reduction Agency aims to print mini organs such as hearts, livers, and lungs as the potential to test new drugs more accurately and perhaps eliminate the need for testing in animals.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting can also be used for cultured meat.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In 2021, a steak-like cultured meat, composed of three types of bovine cell fibers was produced.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The Wagyu-like beef has a structure similar to original meat.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] This technology provides an alternative to natural meat harvesting methods if the livestock industry is plagued by disease.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] In addition, it provides a possible solution to reducing the environmental impact of the livestock industry.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The bioprinting of biofilms uses the same methods as other bioprinting.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Oftentimes, the biofilm begins with an extrusion of a polysaccharide to provide structure for biofilm growth.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] An example of one of these polysaccharides is alginate.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The alginate structure can have microbes embedded within the structure.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Hydrogels can also be used to assist in the formation of functional biofilms.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are difficult to analyze in a laboratory setting due to the complex structure and the time it takes for a functional biofilm to form.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting biofilms allows us to skip certain processes and makes it easier to analyze functional biofilms.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Thickness of the biofilm being printed with change the functionality due to nutrient and oxygen diffusion.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Thicker 3D printed biofilms will naturally select for anaerobes for example.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Biofilms are capable of remediation in the natural environment which suggests there is potential in regards to the use of 3D bioprinted biofilm use in environmental remediation.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Microbes are able to degrade a large range of chemicals and metals and providing a structure for these microbes to flourish such as in biofilm structures is beneficial.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Artificial biofilms protect the microbes from the dangers of the environment while promoting signaling and overall microbial interactions.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] 3D bioprinting allows functional microorganisms to be placed in structures that provide mechanical stability and protects them from environmental conditions.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] The larger contact area provided by 3D printed structures compared to normal environmental structures provides more efficient removal of pollutants.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Bioprinting also has possible uses in the future in assisting in wastewater treatment and in corrosion control.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] When humans come in contact with environmental biofilms, it is possible for infections and long-term health hazards to occur.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Antibiotic penetration and expansion within a biofilm is an area of research which can benefit from bioprinting techniques, to further explore the effect of environmental biofilms on human health.
[src:hospital/3d-bioprinting] Biofilm printing requires further research due to limited published data and complex protocols.
[src:hospital/academic-health-science-centre] AMCs are intended to ensure that medical research breakthroughs lead to direct clinical benefits for patients.
[src:hospital/academic-health-science-centre] The organisational structures that comprise an AMCs can take a variety of forms, ranging from simple partnerships to, less frequently, fully integrated organisations with a single management board.
[src:hospital/academic-health-science-centre] There are AMCs operating in a number of countries including Australia, Canada, Ireland, Japan, the Netherlands, Qatar, Singapore, Sweden, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The **Academy of Gondishapur** or **Academy of Jondishapur** (Persian: فرهنگستان گندی‌شاپور, Farhangestân-e Gondišâpur), also known as the **Gondishapur University**, is a Sassanid-era center of education and academy of learning in Khuzestan, Iran.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] With a history spanning more than 1,700 years, it also included a hospital and a library.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Since its activity was interrupted several times throughout history, Gondishapur is considered the oldest known university in terms of historical origin, while Al-Qarawiyyin in Morocco remains as the world’s oldest continuously operating university.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Founded by the Sassanid king Shapur I, Gondishapur first offered education and training in medicine, philosophy, theology and science.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The modern concept of a hospital as a center for both treatment and medical training took shape here, giving Gondishapur significant influence over the history of medical science.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The academy’s hospital was the most important medical institution in the ancient world during the 6th and 7th centuries AD.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] In 1955 under the Pahlavi dynasty, the Academy received a twin with the establishment of *Ahvaz Jundishapur University of Medical Sciences*, near the city of Ahvaz.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] During the Iran–Iraq War in 1980s, Mostafa Chamran used parts of the university as his command base.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] After his death, in honor of his bravery and sacrifices, the Ahvaz Jundishapur University was renamed to Shahid Chamran University of Ahvaz, while the main university kept its ancient name Gondishapur.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The university's original campus is now an archaeological site, while it continues to operate under the same name in its modern building.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Today, the Gondishapur and Shahid Chamran Universities operate 3 campuses, 9 schools, 15 colleges, and more than 65 hospitals.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The first hospitals of the Islamic period were established based on the model of the Gundishapur hospital.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Nevertheless, the available historical information is insufficient to present a precise picture of the city’s scientific and cultural conditions.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] What Islamic-era sources recount about its scholarly past often borders on legend.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Modern research as well sometimes contains unsubstantiated or exaggerated claims, making it very difficult to determine the accuracy of this information.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Ibn al-Nadim writes that Ardashir I collected all remaining scattered ancient Persian books from India and China and added them to the royal treasury.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] His son, Shapur I, continued this path, gathering all texts that had been translated into Middle Persian from other languages.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] He also compiled the Avesta into a single book, thus restoring it after Alexander had burned it.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Another library built during this period was the library of Khosrow I in Gundishapur, created for the university.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] His well-known passion for collecting books from the farthest regions of the world enriched it greatly.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Gundishapur became the finest research center of the Sassanid era.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Many scholars of diverse backgrounds—especially Nestorians—gathered there, and numerous works were translated into Persian by order of Khosrow I.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Besides these two libraries, other large and reputable libraries also existed; every fire temple and shrine, as well as all hospitals, research institutions, and educational centers, maintained their own collections of books.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] In 489 AD, the East Syriac Christian theological and scientific center in Edessa was ordered closed by the Byzantine emperor Zeno, and was transferred and absorbed into the School of Nisibis in Asia Minor, also known as *Nisibīn*, then under Persian rule.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Here, Nestorian scholars, together with Hellenistic philosophers banished from Athens by Justinian in 529, carried out important research in medicine, astronomy, and mathematics.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] However, it was under the rule of the Sassanid emperor Khosrau I (a.d.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] 531-579), known to the Greeks and Romans as *Chosroes*, that Gondeshapur became known for medicine and learning.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Khosrau I gave refuge to various Greek philosophers and Syriac-speaking Nestorian Christians fleeing religious persecution by the Byzantine Empire.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The Sassanids had long battled the Romans and Byzantines for control of present-day Iraq and Syria and were naturally disposed to welcome the refugees.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Khosrau I also turned towards the east, and sent the physician Borzouye to invite Indian and Chinese scholars to Gondeshapur.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] These visitors translated Indian texts on astronomy, astrology, mathematics and medicine and Chinese texts on herbal medicine and religion.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Emperor Khosrau I commissioned the refugees to translate Greek and Syriac texts into Middle Persian.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] They translated various works on medicine, astronomy, philosophy, and useful crafts.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] A Church of the East monastery was established in the city of Gondishapur sometime before 376/7.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] By the 6th century the city became famed for its theological school where Rabban Hormizd once studied.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] According to a letter from the Catholicos of the East Timothy I, the Metropolitanate of Beth Huzaye took charge of both the theological and medical institutions.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Although almost all the physicians of the medical academy were Persians, yet they wrote their treatises in Syriac, because medicine had a literary tradition in Syriac.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] At the Academy of Gundishapur during the Sassanid era, there was a dedicated department focused on collecting information about the illnesses of seafarers and methods for treating them.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] During the exploratory naval expeditions of the Achaemenid period, physicians accompanied the fleets to provide medical care for sailors.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] In addition to systemizing medical treatment and knowledge, the scholars of the academy also transformed medical education; rather than apprenticing with just one physician, medical students were required to work in the hospital under the supervision of the whole medical faculty.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] There is even evidence that graduates had to pass exams in order to practice as accredited Gondeshapur physicians (as recorded in an Arabic text, the *Tārīkh al-ḥukamā*).
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] While there are no extant records relating to mathematical activities in Gondeshapur, it is probable that works on mathematics were translated there alongside texts from other disciplines.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] In 832 AD, Caliph al-Ma'mūn bolstered the famous House of Wisdom.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] There the methods of Gondeshapur were emulated; indeed, the House of Wisdom was staffed with graduates of the older Academy of Gondeshapur.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] However, by that time the intellectual center of the Abbasid Caliphate had definitively shifted to Baghdad, as henceforth there are few references in contemporary literature to universities or hospitals at Gondeshapur.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The significance of the center gradually declined.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Al-Muqaddasi's *Best Divisions for Knowledge of the Regions* (c.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] 1000 AD) described Gondeshapur as falling into ruins.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The last known head of Gundeshapur's hospital died in 869 AD.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Under the Pahlavi dynasty, the heritage of Gondeshapur was memorialized by the founding of the *Jondishapur University* and its twin institution *Jondishapur University of Medical Sciences*, near the city of Ahvaz in 1955.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The latter-day Jondishapur University of Medical Sciences was founded and named after its Sassanid predecessor, by its founder and first Chancellor, Dr.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Mohammad Kar, Father of Cyrus Kar, in Ahvaz in 1959.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] The first woman to be appointed as vice-chancellor in a university in Iran, Dr.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Tal'at Basari, was appointed at this university in the mid-1960s, and starting 1968, plans for the modern campus were designed by famed architect Kamran Diba.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Ancient Gondeshapur is also slated for an archaeological investigation.
[src:hospital/academy-of-guneshapur] Experts from the Archaeological Research Center of Iran's Cultural Heritage Organization and the Oriental Institute of the University of Chicago plan to start excavations in early 2006.
[src:hospital/acute-care] Acute care services are generally delivered by teams of health care professionals from a range of medical and surgical specialties.
[src:hospital/acute-care] Acute care may require a stay in a hospital emergency department, ambulatory surgery center, urgent care centre or other short-term stay facility, along with the assistance of diagnostic services, surgery, or follow-up outpatient care in the community.
[src:hospital/acute-care] Hospital-based acute inpatient care typically has the goal of discharging patients as soon as they are deemed healthy and stable.
[src:hospital/acute-care] Acute care settings include emergency department, intensive care, coronary care, cardiology, neonatal intensive care, and many general areas where the patient could become acutely unwell and require stabilization and transfer to another higher dependency unit for further treatment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The **Age of Enlightenment**, also known as the **Age of Reason** or simply **the Enlightenment**, was a period of intellectual and cultural flourishing in Europe and Western civilization, emerging in the late 17th century in Western Europe.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It reached its peak in the 18th century as its ideas spread more widely across Europe and into the European colonies in the Americas and Oceania.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Characterized by an emphasis on reason, empirical evidence, and the scientific method, the Enlightenment promoted ideals of individual liberty, religious tolerance, progress, and natural rights.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Its thinkers advocated for constitutional government, the separation of church and state, and the application of rational principles to social and political reform.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment emerged from and built upon the Scientific Revolution of the 16th and 17th centuries, which had established new methods of empirical inquiry through the work of figures such as Galileo Galilei, Johannes Kepler, Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, Christiaan Huygens, and Isaac Newton.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Philosophical foundations were laid by thinkers including René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, and John Locke, whose ideas about reason, natural rights, and empirical knowledge became central to Enlightenment thought.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Others cite the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687) as the culmination of the Scientific Revolution and the beginning of the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European historians traditionally dated its beginning with the death of Louis XIV of France in 1715 and its end with the outbreak of the French Revolution in 1789.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many historians now date the end of the Enlightenment as the start of the 19th century, with the latest proposed year being the death of Immanuel Kant in 1804.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The movement was characterized by the widespread circulation of ideas through new institutions: scientific academies, literary salons, coffeehouses, Masonic lodges, and an expanding print culture of books, journals, and pamphlets.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The ideas of the Enlightenment undermined the authority of the monarchy and religious officials and paved the way for the political revolutions of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A variety of 19th-century movements, including liberalism, socialism, and neoclassicism, trace their intellectual heritage to the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] By contrast, other intellectual currents included arguments in favour of anti-Christianity, Deism and Atheism, accompanied by demands for secular states, bans on religious education, suppression of monasteries, the suppression of the Jesuits, and the expulsion of religious orders.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment also faced contemporary criticism, later termed the "Counter-Enlightenment" by Sir Isaiah Berlin, which defended traditional religious and political authorities against rationalist critique.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment was preceded by and closely associated with the Scientific Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Earlier philosophers whose work influenced the Enlightenment included Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, Pierre Bayle, and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some of the figures of the Enlightenment included Cesare Beccaria, George Berkeley, Denis Diderot, David Hume, Immanuel Kant, Lord Monboddo, Montesquieu, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Adam Smith, Roger Williams, Hugo Grotius, and Voltaire.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] One of the most influential Enlightenment publications was the **Encyclopédie** (*Encyclopedia*).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Published between 1751 and 1772 in 35 volumes, it was compiled by Diderot, Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and a team of 150 others.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The *Encyclopédie* helped spread the ideas of the Enlightenment across Europe and beyond.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bacon's empiricism and Descartes' rationalist philosophy laid the foundation for enlightenment thinking.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' attempt to construct the sciences on a secure metaphysical foundation was not as successful as his method of doubt applied to philosophy, which led to a dualistic doctrine of mind and matter.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His skepticism was refined by Locke's *Essay Concerning Human Understanding* (1690) and Hume's writings in the 1740s.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' dualism was challenged by Spinoza's uncompromising assertion of the unity of matter in his *Tractatus* (1670) and *Ethics* (1677).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The moderate variety tended to be deistic whereas the radical tendency separated the basis of morality entirely from theology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both lines of thought were eventually opposed by a conservative Counter-Enlightenment which sought a return to faith.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the mid-18th century, Paris became the center of philosophic and scientific activity challenging traditional doctrines and dogmas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] After the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, the relationship between church and the absolutist government was very strong.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The early enlightenment emerged in protest to these circumstances, gaining ground under the support of Madame de Pompadour, the mistress of Louis XV.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Called the *Siècle des Lumières,* the philosophical movement of the Enlightenment had already started by the early 18th century, when Pierre Bayle launched the popular and scholarly Enlightenment critique of religion.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As a skeptic Bayle only partially accepted the philosophy and principles of rationality.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He did draw a strict boundary between morality and religion.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The political philosopher Montesquieu introduced the idea of a separation of powers in a government, a concept which was enthusiastically adopted by the authors of the United States Constitution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the *philosophes* of the French Enlightenment were not revolutionaries and many were members of the nobility, their ideas played an important part in undermining the legitimacy of the Old Regime and shaping the French Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume became a major figure in the skeptical philosophical and empiricist traditions of philosophy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom and political authority, as well as map out a view of the public sphere through private and public reason.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant's work continued to influence German intellectual life and European philosophy more broadly well into the 20th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Mary Wollstonecraft was one of England's earliest feminist philosophers.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She argued for a society based on reason and that women as well as men should be treated as rational beings.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She is best known for her 1792 work, *A Vindication of the Rights of Woman*.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science played an important role in Enlightenment discourse and thought.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many Enlightenment writers and thinkers had backgrounds in the sciences and associated scientific advancement with the overthrow of religion and traditional authority in favour of the development of free speech and thought.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The experiments of Antoine Lavoisier were used to create the first modern chemical plants in Paris, and the experiments of the Montgolfier brothers enabled them to launch the first manned flight in a hot air balloon in 1783.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Broadly speaking, Enlightenment science greatly valued empiricism and rational thought and was embedded with the Enlightenment ideal of advancement and progress.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The study of science, under the heading of natural philosophy, was divided into physics and a conglomerate grouping of chemistry and natural history, which included anatomy, biology, geology, mineralogy, and zoology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As with most Enlightenment views, the benefits of science were not seen universally: Rousseau criticized the sciences for distancing man from nature and not operating to make people happier.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science during the Enlightenment was dominated by scientific societies and academies, which had largely replaced universities as centres of scientific research and development.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Societies and academies were also the backbone of the maturation of the scientific profession.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Scientific academies and societies grew out of the Scientific Revolution as the creators of scientific knowledge, in contrast to the scholasticism of the university.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some societies created or retained links to universities, but contemporary sources distinguished universities from scientific societies by claiming that the university's utility was in the transmission of knowledge while societies functioned to create knowledge.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As the role of universities in institutionalized science began to diminish, learned societies became the cornerstone of organized science.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Official scientific societies were chartered by the state to provide technical expertise.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Most societies were granted permission to oversee their own publications, control the election of new members and the administration of the society.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the 18th century, a very large number of official academies and societies were founded in Europe; by 1789 there were over 70 official scientific societies.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In reference to this growth, Bernard de Fontenelle coined the term "the Age of Academies" to describe the 18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Another important development was the popularization of science among an increasingly literate population.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] *Philosophes* introduced the public to many scientific theories, most notably through the *Encyclopédie* and the popularization of Newtonianism by Voltaire and Émilie du Châtelet.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some historians have marked the 18th century as a drab period in the history of science.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The century saw significant advancements in the practice of medicine, mathematics, and physics; the development of biological taxonomy; a new understanding of magnetism and electricity; and the maturation of chemistry as a discipline, which established the foundations of modern chemistry.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The influence of science began appearing more commonly in poetry and literature.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While some societies were established with ties to universities or maintained existing ones contemporary sources often distinguished between the two, asserting that universities primarily served to transmit knowledge, whereas scientific societies were oriented toward the creation of new knowledge.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] James Thomson penned his "A Poem to the Memory of Sir Isaac Newton," which mourned the loss of Newton and praised his science and legacy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Modern sociology largely originated from this movement, and Hume's philosophical concepts that directly influenced James Madison (and thus the U.S.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution), and as popularised by Dugald Stewart was the basis of classical liberalism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In 1776, Adam Smith published *The Wealth of Nations,* often considered the first work on modern economics as it had an immediate impact on British economic policy that continues into the 21st century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It was immediately preceded and influenced by Anne Robert Jacques Turgot's drafts of *Reflections on the Formation and Distribution of Wealth* (1766).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Smith acknowledged indebtedness and possibly was the original English translator.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Beccaria, a jurist, criminologist, philosopher, and politician and one of the great Enlightenment writers, became famous for his masterpiece *Dei delitti e delle pene* (Of Crimes and Punishments, 1764).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His treatise, translated into 22 languages, condemned torture and the death penalty and was a founding work in the field of penology and the classical school of criminology by promoting criminal justice.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Francesco Mario Pagano wrote studies such as *Saggi politici* (Political Essays, 1783); and *Considerazioni sul processo criminale* (Considerations on the Criminal Trial, 1787), which established him as an international authority on criminal law.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has long been seen as the foundation of modern Western political and intellectual culture.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment brought political modernization to the West, in terms of introducing democratic values and institutions and the creation of modern, liberal democracies.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This thesis has been widely accepted by scholars and has been reinforced by the large-scale studies by Robert Darnton, Roy Porter, and, most recently, by Jonathan Israel.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment thought was deeply influential in the political realm.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European rulers such as Catherine II of Russia, Joseph II of Austria, and Frederick II of Prussia tried to apply Enlightenment thought on religious and political tolerance, which became known as enlightened absolutism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution during its framing in 1787.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke, one of the most influential Enlightenment thinkers, based his governance philosophy on social contract theory, a subject that permeated Enlightenment political thought.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] English philosopher Thomas Hobbes ushered in this new debate with his work *Leviathan* in 1651.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Locke and Rousseau developed social contract theories in *Two Treatises of Government* and *Discourse on Inequality*, respectively.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While quite different works, Locke, Hobbes, and Rousseau agreed that a social contract, in which the government's authority lies in the consent of the governed, is necessary for man to live in civil society.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke defines the state of nature as a condition in which humans are rational and follow natural law, in which all men are born equal and with the right to life, liberty, and property.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] However, when one citizen breaks the law of nature both the transgressor and the victim enter into a state of war, from which it is virtually impossible to break free.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore, Locke said that individuals enter into civil society to protect their natural rights via an "unbiased judge" or common authority, such as courts.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In contrast, Rousseau's conception relies on the supposition that "civil man" is corrupted, while "natural man" has no want he cannot fulfill himself.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Natural man is only taken out of the state of nature when the inequality associated with private property is established.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rousseau said that people join into civil society via the social contract to achieve unity while preserving individual freedom.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This is embodied in the sovereignty of the general will, the moral and collective legislative body constituted by citizens.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke is known for his statement that individuals have a right to "Life, Liberty, and Property," and his belief that the natural right to property is derived from labor.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Declaration of Independence and the French National Constituent Assembly's Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some *philosophes* argued that the establishment of a contractual basis of rights would lead to the market mechanism and capitalism, the scientific method, religious tolerance, and the organization of states into self-governing republics through democratic means.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In this view, the tendency of the *philosophes* in particular to apply rationality to every problem is considered the essential change.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Although much of Enlightenment political thought was dominated by social contract theorists, Hume and Ferguson criticized this camp.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume's essay *Of the Original Contract* argues that governments derived from consent are rarely seen and civil government is grounded in a ruler's habitual authority and force.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It is precisely because of the ruler's authority over-and-against the subject that the subject tacitly consents, and Hume says that the subjects would "never imagine that their consent made him sovereign," rather the authority did so.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Similarly, Ferguson did not believe citizens built the state, rather polities grew out of social development.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In his 1767 *An Essay on the History of Civil Society,* Ferguson uses the four stages of progress, a theory that was popular in Scotland at the time, to explain how humans advance from a hunting and gathering society to a commercial and civil society without agreeing to a social contract.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Rousseau's and Locke's social contract theories rest on the presupposition of natural rights, which are not a result of law or custom but are things that all men have in pre-political societies and are therefore universal and inalienable.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The most famous natural right formulation comes from Locke's *Second Treatise,* when he introduces the state of nature.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, the law of nature is grounded on mutual security or the idea that one cannot infringe on another's natural rights, as every man is equal and has the same inalienable rights.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These natural rights include perfect equality and freedom, as well as the right to preserve life and property.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues against indentured servitude on the basis that enslaving oneself goes against the law of nature because a person cannot surrender their own rights: freedom is absolute, and no one can take it away.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues that one person cannot enslave another because it is morally reprehensible, although he introduces a caveat by saying that enslavement of a lawful captive in time of war would not go against one's natural rights.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The leaders of the Enlightenment were not especially democratic, as they more often look to absolute monarchs as the key to imposing reforms designed by the intellectuals.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In several nations, rulers welcomed leaders of the Enlightenment at court and asked them to help design laws and programs to reform the system, typically to build stronger states.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These rulers are called "enlightened despots" by historians.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They included Frederick the Great of Prussia, Catherine the Great of Russia, Leopold II of Tuscany and Joseph II of Austria.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Joseph was over-enthusiastic, announcing many reforms that had little support so that revolts broke out and his regime became a comedy of errors, and nearly all his programs were reversed.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Senior ministers Pombal in Portugal and Johann Friedrich Struensee in Denmark also governed according to Enlightenment ideals.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In Poland, the model constitution of 1791 expressed Enlightenment ideals, but was in effect for only one year before the nation was partitioned among its neighbors.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] More enduring were the cultural achievements, which created a nationalist spirit in Poland.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Frederick the Great, the king of Prussia from 1740 to 1786, saw himself as a leader of the Enlightenment and patronized philosophers and scientists at his court in Berlin.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Voltaire, who had been imprisoned and maltreated by the French government, was eager to accept Frederick's invitation to live at his palace.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has been frequently linked to the American Revolution of 1776 and the French Revolution of 1789—both had some intellectual influence from Thomas Jefferson.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A key aspect of this era was a profound shift from the absolute monarchies of Europe, which asserted the "divine right" to rule.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] John Locke rejected this view in his writings on the Two Treatises of Government (1689).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He asserted that citizens were seen to possess natural rights, including life, liberty, and property.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore governments exist to protect these rights through the "consent of the governed." The clash between these competing ethos often resulted in violent upheaval in differing ways.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In France, Ancien régime, with its rigid social hierarchy and absolute monarchical power, was systematically dismantled during the French Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the American Revolution focused more on breaking free from a government - represented by King George III and Parliament - that colonists felt did not adequately represent their interests.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Alexis de Tocqueville proposed the French Revolution as the inevitable result of the radical opposition created in the 18th century between the monarchy and the men of letters of the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These men of letters constituted a sort of "substitute aristocracy that was both all-powerful and without real power." This illusory power came from the rise of "public opinion," born when absolutist centralization removed the nobility and the bourgeoisie from the political sphere.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "literary politics" that resulted promoted a discourse of equality and was hence in fundamental opposition to the monarchical regime.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment era religious commentary was a response to the preceding century of religious conflict in Europe, especially the Thirty Years' War.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Theologians of the Enlightenment wanted to reform their faith to its generally non-confrontational roots and to limit the capacity for religious controversy to spill over into politics and warfare while still maintaining a true faith in God.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For moderate Christians, this meant a return to simple Scripture.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke abandoned the corpus of theological commentary in favor of an "unprejudiced examination" of the Word of God alone.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He determined the essence of Christianity to be a belief in Christ the redeemer and recommended avoiding more detailed debate.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the *Jefferson Bible,* Thomas Jefferson went further and dropped any passages dealing with miracles, visitations of angels, and the resurrection of Jesus after his death, as he tried to extract the practical Christian moral code of the New Testament.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment scholars sought to curtail the political power of organized religion and thereby prevent another age of intolerant religious war.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Spinoza determined to remove politics from contemporary and historical theology (e.g., disregarding Judaic law).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Moses Mendelssohn advised affording no political weight to any organized religion but instead recommended that each person follow what they found most convincing.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They believed a good religion based in instinctive morals and a belief in God should not theoretically need force to maintain order in its believers, and both Mendelssohn and Spinoza judged religion on its moral fruits, not the logic of its theology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Several novel ideas about religion developed with the Enlightenment, including deism and talk of atheism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to Thomas Paine, deism is the simple belief in God the Creator with no reference to the Bible or any other miraculous source.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Instead, the deist relies solely on personal reason to guide his creed, which was eminently agreeable to many thinkers of the time.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Atheism was much discussed, but there were few proponents.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Wilson and Reill note: "In fact, very few enlightened intellectuals, even when they were vocal critics of Christianity, were true atheists.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rather, they were critics of orthodox belief, wedded rather to skepticism, deism, vitalism, or perhaps pantheism." Some followed Pierre Bayle and argued that atheists could indeed be moral men.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many others like Voltaire held that without belief in a God who punishes evil, the moral order of society was undermined; that is, since atheists gave themselves to no supreme authority and no law and had no fear of eternal consequences, they were far more likely to disrupt society.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bayle observed that, in his day, "prudent persons will always maintain an appearance of [religion]," and he believed that even atheists could hold concepts of honor and go beyond their own self-interest to create and interact in society.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke said that if there were no God and no divine law, the result would be moral anarchy: every individual "could have no law but his own will, no end but himself.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "Radical Enlightenment" promoted the concept of separating church and state, an idea that is often credited to Locke.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to his principle of the social contract, Locke said that the government lacked authority in the realm of individual conscience, as this was something rational people could not cede to the government for it or others to control.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, this created a natural right in the liberty of conscience, which he said must therefore remain protected from any government authority.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These views on religious tolerance and the importance of individual conscience, along with the social contract, became particularly influential in the American colonies and the drafting of the United States Constitution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in Connecticut, Thomas Jefferson calls for a "wall of separation between church and state" at the federal level.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He previously had supported successful efforts to disestablish the Church of England in Virginia and authored the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Jefferson's political ideals were greatly influenced by the writings of Locke, Bacon, and Newton, whom he considered the three greatest men that ever lived.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment took hold in most European countries and influenced nations globally, often with a specific local emphasis.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] For example, in France it became associated with anti-government and anti-Church radicalism, while in Germany it reached deep into the middle classes, where it expressed a spiritualistic and nationalistic tone without threatening governments or established churches.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, the government was hostile, and the *philosophes* fought against its censorship, sometimes being imprisoned or hounded into exile.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The British government, for the most part, ignored the Enlightenment's leaders in England and Scotland, although it did give Newton a knighthood and a very lucrative government office.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A common theme among most countries which derived Enlightenment ideas from Europe was the intentional non-inclusion of Enlightenment philosophies pertaining to slavery.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1791, the Haitian Revolution, a slave rebellion by emancipated slaves against French colonial rule in the colony of Saint-Domingue, broke out.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The very existence of an English Enlightenment has been hotly debated by scholars.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The majority of textbooks on British history make little or no mention of an English Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Some surveys of the entire Enlightenment include England and others ignore it, although they do include coverage of such major intellectuals as Joseph Addison, Edward Gibbon, John Locke, Isaac Newton, Alexander Pope, Joshua Reynolds, and Jonathan Swift.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freethinking, a term describing those who stood in opposition to the institution of the Church, and the literal belief in the Bible, can be said to have begun in England no later than 1713, when Anthony Collins wrote his "Discourse of Free-thinking," which gained substantial popularity.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This essay attacked the clergy of all churches and was a plea for deism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Roy Porter argues that the reasons for this neglect were the assumptions that the movement was primarily French-inspired, that it was largely a-religious or anti-clerical, and that it stood in outspoken defiance to the established order.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter admits that after the 1720s England could claim thinkers to equal Diderot, Voltaire, or Rousseau.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, its leading intellectuals such as Gibbon, Edmund Burke and Samuel Johnson were all quite conservative and supportive of the standing order.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter says the reason was that Enlightenment had come early to England and had succeeded such that the culture had accepted political liberalism, philosophical empiricism, and religious toleration, positions which intellectuals on the continent had to fight against powerful odds.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Furthermore, England rejected the collectivism of the continent and emphasized the improvement of individuals as the main goal of enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Derek Hirst, the 1640s and 1650s saw a revived economy characterised by growth in manufacturing, the elaboration of financial and credit instruments, and the commercialisation of communication.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The gentry found time for leisure activities, such as horse racing and bowling.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the high culture important innovations included the development of a mass market for music, increased scientific research, and an expansion of publishing.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] All the trends were discussed in depth at the newly established coffee houses.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the Scottish Enlightenment, the principles of sociability, equality, and utility were disseminated in schools and universities, many of which used sophisticated teaching methods which blended philosophy with daily life.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scotland's major cities created an intellectual infrastructure of mutually supporting institutions such as schools, universities, reading societies, libraries, periodicals, museums, and Masonic lodges.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Several Americans, especially Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson, played a major role in bringing Enlightenment ideas to the New World and in influencing British and French thinkers.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin was influential for his political activism and for his advances in physics.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin also broadly encouraged the individual's rights and responsibilities to serve as an educated and informed citizen.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He published yearly the widely popular, *Poor Richard's Almanack,* filled with witty quotes encouraging disciplined self-learning, such as "Early to bed, early to rise, makes a man healthy, wealthy and wise." The cultural exchange during the Enlightenment ran in both directions across the Atlantic.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Thinkers such as Paine, Locke, and Rousseau all take Native American cultural practices as examples of natural freedom.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Americans closely followed English and Scottish political ideas, as well as some French thinkers such as Montesquieu.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] As deists, they were influenced by ideas of John Toland and Matthew Tindal.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was a great emphasis upon liberty, republicanism, and religious tolerance.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was no respect for monarchy or inherited political power.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Deists reconciled science and religion by rejecting prophecies, miracles, and biblical theology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leading deists included Thomas Paine in *The Age of Reason* and Thomas Jefferson in his short *Jefferson Bible,* from which he removed all supernatural aspects.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Jewish Enlightenment, or *Haskalah* (Hebrew: הַשְׂכָּלָה, "education") was an intellectual movement among the Jews of Central and Eastern Europe, with a certain influence on those in Western Europe and the Muslim world.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It arose as a defined ideological worldview during the 1770s, and its last stage ended around 1881, with the rise of Jewish nationalism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement advocated against Jewish reclusiveness, encouraged the adoption of prevalent attire over traditional dress, while also working to diminish the authority of traditional community institutions such as rabbinic courts and boards of elders.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Early Dutch Enlightenment (1640–1720), many books were translated from Latin, French or English to Dutch, often at the risk of their translators and publishers.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the 1720s, the Dutch Republic had also become a major center for printing and exporting banned books to France.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Implanted in Netherlandish culture, vernacular rationalism brought the Dutch to take advantage of the intellectual philosophy the enlightenment spread.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The most famous figure of the Dutch Enlightenment was Baruch Spinoza.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The French Enlightenment was influenced by England and in turn influenced other national enlightenments.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Prussia took the lead among the German states in sponsoring the political reforms that Enlightenment thinkers urged absolute rulers to adopt.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There were important movements as well in the smaller states of Bavaria, Saxony, Hanover, and the Palatinate.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In each case, Enlightenment values became accepted and led to significant political and administrative reforms that laid the groundwork for the creation of modern states.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The princes of Saxony, for example, carried out an impressive series of fundamental fiscal, administrative, judicial, educational, cultural, and general economic reforms.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reforms were aided by the country's strong urban structure and influential commercial groups and modernized pre-1789 Saxony along the lines of classic Enlightenment principles.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Before 1750, the German upper classes looked to France for intellectual, cultural, and architectural leadership, as French was the language of high society.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the mid-18th century, the *Aufklärung* (The Enlightenment) had transformed German high culture in music, philosophy, science, and literature.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Christian Wolff was the pioneer as a writer who expounded the Enlightenment to German readers and legitimized German as a philosophic language.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Johann Gottfried von Herder broke new ground in philosophy and poetry, as a leader of the Sturm und Drang movement of proto-Romanticism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Weimar Classicism (*Weimarer Klassik*) was a cultural and literary movement based in Weimar that sought to establish a new humanism by synthesizing Romantic, classical, and Enlightenment ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement (from 1772 until 1805) involved Herder as well as polymath Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Friedrich Schiller, a poet and historian.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The theatre principal Abel Seyler greatly influenced the development of German theatre and promoted serious German opera, new works and experimental productions, and the concept of a national theatre.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Herder argued that every group of people had its own particular identity, which was expressed in its language and culture.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This legitimized the promotion of German language and culture and helped shape the development of German nationalism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Schiller's plays expressed the restless spirit of his generation, depicting the hero's struggle against social pressures and the force of destiny.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German music, sponsored by the upper classes, came of age under composers Johann Sebastian Bach, Joseph Haydn, and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In remote Königsberg, Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom, and political authority.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Kant's work contained basic tensions that would continue to shape German thought—and indeed all of European philosophy—well into the 20th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German Enlightenment won the support of princes, aristocrats, and the middle classes, and it permanently reshaped the culture.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, there was a conservatism among the elites that warned against going too far.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1788, Prussia issued an "Edict on Religion" that forbade preaching any sermon that undermined popular belief in the Holy Trinity or the Bible.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The goal was to avoid theological disputes that might impinge on domestic tranquility.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Men who doubted the value of Enlightenment favoured the measure, but so too did many supporters.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German universities had created a closed elite that could debate controversial issues among themselves, but spreading them to the public was seen as too risky.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This intellectual elite was favoured by the state, but that might be reversed if the process of the Enlightenment proved politically or socially destabilizing.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, Austria was under Habsburg rule.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reign of Maria Theresa, the first Habsburg monarch to be considered influenced by the Enlightenment in some areas, was marked by a mix of enlightenment and conservatism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Her son Joseph II's brief reign was marked by this conflict, with his ideology of Josephinism facing opposition.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph II carried out numerous reforms in the spirit of the Enlightenment, which affected, for example, the school system, monasteries and the legal system.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Emperor Leopold II, who was an early opponent of capital punishment, had a brief and contentious rule that was mostly marked by relations with France.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Similarly, Emperor Francis II's rule was primarily marked by relations with France.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment also appeared in literature and theater works.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph von Sonnenfels was an important representative.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In music, Austrian musicians such as Joseph Haydn and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart were associated with the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Modern Greek Enlightenment (Greek: Διαφωτισμός, Diafotismós) was the Greek expression of the Enlightenment, characterized by an intellectual and philosophical movement within the Greek community.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At this time, many Greeks were dispersed across the Ottoman Empire, with some residing on the Ionian Islands, in Venice, and other parts of Italy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century, while Hungary was part of the Habsburg Empire.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment is usually said to have begun in 1772 and was greatly influenced by French Enlightenment (through Vienna).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Romanian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century across the three major historical regions inhabited by Romanians: Transylvania, Wallachia, and Moldavia.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At that time, Transylvania was in the Habsburg Empire while Wallachia and Moldavia were vassals of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Transylvanian Enlightenment was represented by the Transylvanian School, a group of thinkers who promoted a cultural revival and rights for Romanians (who were marginalized by the Habsburgs).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Wallachian Enlightenment was represented by such figures as Dinicu Golescu (1777–1830), while the Moldavian Englightenment was headed by prince Dimitrie Cantemir (1673-1723).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment arrived relatively late in Switzerland, spreading from England, the Netherlands, and France toward the end of the 17th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement initially took hold in Protestant regions, where it gradually replaced orthodox religious thinking.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The 1712 victory of the reformed cantons of Zurich and Bern over the five Catholic cantons of central Switzerland in the Second War of Villmergen marked both a Protestant triumph and a victory for Enlightenment ideas in the economically more developed regions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Switzerland, which lacked a central court or academy, the Enlightenment spread through the intellectual elite of reformed cities, particularly pastors educated in academies and colleges with strong humanist traditions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss Enlightenment thinkers made significant contributions across multiple fields.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, Johann Jakob Bodmer and Johann Jakob Breitinger made Zurich a center of German literary innovation, while Albert von Haller's poetry represented the peak of Swiss Enlightenment literature.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean-Jacques Rousseau, considering himself both a Genevan and Swiss citizen, developed democratic republican theories that extended Genevan models to broader European federalist principles.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement was characterized by what scholars term "Helvetism" – specifically Swiss aspects including a Christian conception of natural law, patriotic ethics, and philosophical approaches grounded in practical pedagogy and economics.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most distinctively, Swiss Enlightenment thought celebrated Alpine nature, viewing Switzerland as the "land of shepherds" whose republican and federalist traditions were shaped by its mountain environment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement organized through numerous societies and publications, including the *Encyclopédie d'Yverdon* (1770-1780), which offered a moderate alternative to the French *Encyclopédie*.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss intellectuals gained international prominence, with many serving in foreign academies, particularly in Berlin under Frederick II and in St.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Italy, the main centers of diffusion of the Enlightenment were Naples and Milan: in both cities the intellectuals took public office and collaborated with the Bourbon and Habsburg administrations.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Naples, Antonio Genovesi, Ferdinando Galiani, and Gaetano Filangieri were active under the tolerant King Charles of Bourbon.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, the Neapolitan Enlightenment, like Vico's philosophy, remained almost always in the theoretical field.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Only later, many Enlighteners animated the unfortunate experience of the Parthenopean Republic.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Milan, however, the movement strove to find concrete solutions to problems.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The center of discussions was the magazine *Il Caffè* (1762–1766), founded by brothers Pietro and Alessandro Verri (famous philosophers and writers, as well as their brother Giovanni), who also gave life to the Accademia dei Pugni, founded in 1761.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Minor centers were Tuscany, Veneto, and Piedmont, where among others, Pompeo Neri worked.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Naples, Genovesi influenced a generation of southern Italian intellectuals and university students.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His textbook *Della diceosina, o sia della Filosofia del Giusto e dell'Onesto* (1766) was a controversial attempt to mediate between the history of moral philosophy on the one hand and the specific problems encountered by 18th-century commercial society on the other.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It contained the greater part of Genovesi's political, philosophical, and economic thought, which became a guidebook for Neapolitan economic and social development.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Science flourished as Alessandro Volta and Luigi Galvani made break-through discoveries in electricity.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Pietro Verri was a leading economist in Lombardy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Historian Joseph Schumpeter states he was "the most important pre-Smithian authority on Cheapness-and-Plenty." The most influential scholar on the Italian Enlightenment has been Franco Venturi.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Italy also produced some of the Enlightenment's greatest legal theorists, including Cesare Beccaria, Giambattista Vico, and Francesco Mario Pagano.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Charles II, the last Spanish Habsburg monarch, died his successor was from the French House of Bourbon, initiating a period of French Enlightenment influence in Spain and the Spanish Empire.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 18th Century, the Spanish continued to expand their empire in the Americas with the Spanish missions in California and established missions deeper inland in South America.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Under Charles III, the crown began to implement serious structural changes.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The monarchy curtailed the power of the Catholic Church, and established a standing military in Spanish America.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freer trade was promoted under *comercio libre* in which regions could trade with companies sailing from any other Spanish port, rather than the restrictive mercantile system.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The crown sent out scientific expeditions to assert Spanish sovereignty over territories it claimed but did not control, but also importantly to discover the economic potential of its far-flung empire.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Botanical expeditions sought plants that could be of use to the empire.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Charles IV gave Prussian scientist Alexander von Humboldt free rein to travel in Spanish America, usually closed to foreigners, and more importantly, access to crown officials to aid the success of his scientific expedition.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Napoleon invaded Spain in 1808, Ferdinand VII abdicated and Napoleon placed his brother Joseph Bonaparte on the throne.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] To add legitimacy to this move, the Bayonne Constitution was promulgated, which included representation from Spain's overseas components, but most Spaniards rejected the whole Napoleonic project.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Cortes de Cádiz (parliament) was convened to rule Spain in the absence of the legitimate monarch, Ferdinand.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The constitution was in effect from 1812 until 1814, when Napoleon was defeated and Ferdinand was restored to the throne of Spain.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Upon his return, Ferdinand repudiated the constitution and reestablished absolutist rule.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Haitian Revolution began in 1791 and ended in 1804 and shows how Enlightenment ideas "were part of complex transcultural flows." Radical ideas in Paris during and after the French Revolution were mobilized in Haiti, such as by Toussaint Louverture.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Portuguese Enlightenment was heavily marked by the rule of Prime Minister Marquis of Pombal under King Joseph I from 1756 to 1777.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His urbanistic ideas, also being the first large-scale example of earthquake engineering, became collectively known as Pombaline style, and were implemented throughout the kingdom during his stay in office.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His governance was as enlightened as ruthless, see for example the Távora affair.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, the first Enlightenment ideas in Portugal can be traced back to the diplomat, philosopher, and writer António Vieira who spent a considerable amount of his life in colonial Brazil denouncing discriminations against New Christians and the indigenous peoples in Brazil.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, enlightened literary movements such as the Arcádia Lusitana (lasting from 1756 until 1776, then replaced by the Nova Arcádia in 1790 until 1794) surfaced in the academic medium, in particular involving former students of the University of Coimbra.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A distinct member of this group was the poet Manuel Maria Barbosa du Bocage.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The physician António Nunes Ribeiro Sanches was also an important Enlightenment figure, contributing to the *Encyclopédie* and being part of the Russian court.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment influenced various economists and anti-colonial intellectuals throughout the Portuguese Empire, such as José de Azeredo Coutinho, José da Silva Lisboa, Cláudio Manoel da Costa, and Tomás Antônio Gonzaga.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Napoleonic invasion of Portugal had consequences for the Portuguese monarchy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] With the aid of the British navy, the Portuguese royal family was evacuated to Brazil, its most important colony.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Even though Napoleon had been defeated, the royal court remained in Brazil.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Liberal Revolution of 1820 forced the return of the royal family to Portugal.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The terms by which the restored king was to rule was a constitutional monarchy under the Constitution of Portugal.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Brazil declared its independence from Portugal in 1822 and became a monarchy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The existence of a Swedish Enlightenment has been debated by scholars.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Between 1718 and 1772, the Swedish Enlightenment overlapped with the period of parliamentary rule known in Swedish history as the Age of Liberty.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Russia, the government began to actively encourage the proliferation of arts and sciences in the mid-18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This era produced the first Russian university, library, theatre, public museum, and independent press.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Like other enlightened despots, Catherine the Great played a key role in fostering the arts, sciences and education.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] She used her own interpretation of Enlightenment ideals, assisted by notable international experts such as Voltaire (by correspondence) and in residence world class scientists such as Leonhard Euler and Peter Simon Pallas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The national Enlightenment differed from its Western European counterpart in that it promoted further modernization of all aspects of Russian life and was concerned with attacking the institution of serfdom in Russia.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Russian Enlightenment centered on the individual instead of societal enlightenment and encouraged the living of an enlightened life.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A powerful element was *prosveshchenie* which combined religious piety, erudition, and commitment to the spread of learning.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, it lacked the skeptical and critical spirit of the Western European Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment ideas (*oświecenie*) emerged late in Poland, as the Polish middle class was weaker and szlachta (nobility) culture (Sarmatism) together with the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth political system (Golden Liberty) were in deep crisis.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The political system was built on aristocratic republicanism, but was unable to defend itself against powerful neighbors Russia, Prussia, and Austria as they repeatedly sliced off regions until nothing was left of independent Poland.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Polish Enlightenment began in the 1730s–40s and especially in theatre and the arts peaked in the reign of King Stanisław August Poniatowski (second half of the 18th century).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Warsaw was a main centre after 1750, with an expansion of schools and educational institutions and the arts patronage held at the Royal Castle.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leaders promoted tolerance and more education.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] They included King Stanislaw II August and reformers Piotr Switkowski, Antoni Poplawski, Josef Niemcewicz, and Jósef Pawlinkowski, as well as Baudouin de Cortenay, a Polonized dramatist.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Opponents included Florian Jaroszewicz, Gracjan Piotrowski, Karol Wyrwicz, and Wojciech Skarszewski.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement went into decline with the Third Partition of Poland (1795) – a national tragedy inspiring a short period of sentimental writing – and ended in 1822, replaced by Romanticism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From 1641 to 1853, the Tokugawa shogunate of Japan enforced a policy called *kaikin.* The policy prohibited foreign contact with most outside countries.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During this time, Korea "aimed at isolation" and was known as the "hermit kingdom" but became awakened to Enlightenment ideas by the 1890s such as with the activities of the Independence Club.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Korea was influenced by China and Japan but also found its own Enlightenment path with the Korean intellectual Yu Kilchun who popularized the term Enlightenment throughout Korea.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 18th-century India, Tipu Sultan was an enlightened monarch, who "was one of the founding members of the (French) Jacobin Club in Seringapatam, had planted a liberty tree, and asked to be addressed as 'Tipu Citoyen,'" which means Citizen Tipu.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In parts of India, an important movement called the "Bengal Renaissance" led to Enlightenment reforms beginning in the 1820s.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment began to influence the Ottoman Empire in the 1830s and continued into the late 19th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Tanzimat was a period of reform in the Ottoman Empire that began with the Gülhane Hatt-ı Şerif in 1839 and ended with the First Constitutional Era in 1876.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Arab Enlightenment, or *Nahda* (Arabic: النّهضة, "the awakening"), was a cultural movement in Arab-populated regions of the Ottoman Empire such as Egypt, Lebanon, Syria, and Tunisia, during the second half of the 19th century and the early 20th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The *Nahda* is often traced to the cultural shock of the French invasion of Egypt and Syria in 1798, and the reformist drive of subsequent rulers such as Muhammad Ali of Egypt.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The idea of the Enlightenment has always been contested territory.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Keith Thomas, its supporters "hail it as the source of everything that is progressive about the modern world.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From the start, conservative and clerical defenders of traditional religion attacked materialism and skepticism as evil forces that encouraged immorality.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By 1794, they pointed to the Reign of Terror during the French Revolution as confirmation of their predictions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Romantic philosophers argued that the Enlightenment's excessive dependence on reason was a mistake that it perpetuated, disregarding the bonds of history, myth, faith, and tradition that were necessary to hold society together.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Ritchie Robertson portrays it as a grand intellectual and political program, offering a "science" of society modeled on the powerful physical laws of Newton.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] "Social science" was seen as the instrument of human improvement.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It would expose truth and expand human happiness.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The rights of women and non-White people were generally overlooked in Enlightenment philosophy, which is often explicitly Eurocentric.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scientific racism first emerged at this time, bringing together traditional racism and new research methods.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Enlightenment, concepts of monogenism and polygenism became popular, though they would only be systematized epistemologically during the 19th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Monogenism contends that all races have a single origin, while polygenism is the idea that each race has a separate origin.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Until the 18th century, the words "race" and "species" were interchangeable.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The classification of non-European peoples as sub-human and irrational served to justify European dominance.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The term "Enlightenment" emerged in English in the latter part of the 19th century, with particular reference to French philosophy, as the equivalent of the French term *Lumières* (used first by Jean-Baptiste Dubos in 1733 and already well established by 1751).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Kant's 1784 essay "Beantwortung der Frage: Was ist Aufklärung?" ("Answering the Question: What is Enlightenment?"), the German term became *Aufklärung* (*aufklären* = to illuminate; *sich aufklären* = to clear up).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, scholars have never agreed on a definition of the Enlightenment or on its chronological or geographical extent.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Terms like *les Lumières* (French), *illuminism*o (Italian), *ilustración* (Spanish) and *Aufklärung* (German) referred to partly overlapping movements.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment historiography began in the period itself, from what Enlightenment figures said about their work.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A dominant element was the intellectual angle they took.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean le Rond d'Alembert's *Preliminary Discourse* of *l'Encyclopédie* provides a history of the Enlightenment which comprises a chronological list of developments in the realm of knowledge—of which the *Encyclopédie* forms the pinnacle.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1783, Mendelssohn referred to Enlightenment as a process by which man was educated in the use of reason.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Bertrand Russell saw the Enlightenment as a phase in a progressive development which began in antiquity and that reason and challenges to the established order were constant ideals throughout that time.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Although many of these philosophical ideals were picked up by Catholics, Russell argues that by the 18th century the Enlightenment was the principal manifestation of the schism that began with Martin Luther.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jonathan Israel rejects the attempts of postmodern and Marxian historians to understand the revolutionary ideas of the period purely as by-products of social and economic transformations.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He instead focuses on the history of ideas in the period from 1650 to the end of the 18th century and claims that it was the ideas themselves that caused the change that eventually led to the revolutions of the latter half of the 18th century and the early 19th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There is little consensus on the beginning of the Enlightenment, though several historians and philosophers argue that it was marked by Descartes' 1637 philosophy of *Cogito, ergo sum* ("I think, therefore I am"), which shifted the epistemological basis from external authority to internal certainty.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, many cited the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687), which built upon the work of earlier scientists and formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] French historians usually place the *Siècle des Lumières* ("Century of Enlightenments") between 1715 and 1789: from the beginning of the reign of Louis XV until the French Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most scholars use the last years of the century, often choosing the French Revolution or the beginning of the Napoleonic Wars (1804) as a convenient point in time with which to date the end of the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In their 1947 book *Dialectic of Enlightenment,* Frankfurt School philosophers Max Horkheimer and Theodor W.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Extending Horkheimer and Adorno's argument, intellectual historian Jason Josephson Storm argues that any idea of the Enlightenment as a clearly defined period that is separate from the earlier Renaissance and later Romanticism or Counter-Enlightenment constitutes a myth.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Storm defends his categorization of the Enlightenment as "myth" by noting the regulative role ideas of a period of Enlightenment and disenchantment play in modern Western culture, such that belief in magic, spiritualism, and even religion appears somewhat taboo in intellectual strata.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 1970s, study of the Enlightenment expanded to include the ways Enlightenment ideas spread to European colonies and how they interacted with indigenous cultures and how the Enlightenment took place in formerly unstudied areas such as Italy, Greece, the Balkans, Poland, Hungary, and Russia.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Intellectuals such as Robert Darnton and Jürgen Habermas have focused on the social conditions of the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas described the creation of the "bourgeois public sphere" in 18th-century Europe, containing the new venues and modes of communication allowing for rational exchange.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas said that the public sphere was bourgeois, egalitarian, rational, and independent from the state, making it the ideal venue for intellectuals to critically examine contemporary politics and society, away from the interference of established authority.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p02] While the public sphere is generally an integral component of the social study of the Enlightenment, other historians have questioned whether the public sphere had these characteristics.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This approach studies the process of changing sociabilities and cultural practices during the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Elements of the public sphere included that it was egalitarian, that it discussed the domain of "common concern," and that argument was founded on reason.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Habermas uses the term "common concern" to describe those areas of political/social knowledge and discussion that were previously the exclusive territory of the state and religious authorities, now open to critical examination by the public sphere.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The values of this bourgeois public sphere included holding reason to be supreme, considering everything to be open to criticism (the public sphere is critical), and the opposition of secrecy of all sorts.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The creation of the public sphere has been associated with two long-term historical trends: the rise of the modern nation state and the rise of capitalism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The modern nation state in its consolidation of public power created by counterpoint a private realm of society independent of the state, which allowed for the public sphere.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Capitalism also increased society's autonomy and self-awareness, as well as an increasing need for the exchange of information.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the nascent public sphere expanded, it embraced a large variety of institutions, and the most commonly cited were coffee houses and cafés, salons and the literary public sphere, figuratively localized in the Republic of Letters.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the creation of the public sphere was helped by the aristocracy's move from the king's palace at Versailles to Paris in about 1720, since their rich spending stimulated the trade in luxuries and artistic creations, especially fine paintings.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The word "public" implies the highest level of inclusivity—the public sphere by definition should be open to all.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, this sphere was only public to relative degrees.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Cross-class influences occurred through noble and lower class participation in areas such as the coffeehouses and the Masonic lodges.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Because of the focus on reason over superstition, the Enlightenment cultivated the arts.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Emphasis on learning, art, and music became more widespread, especially with the growing middle class.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Areas of study such as literature, philosophy, science, and the fine arts increasingly explored subject matter to which the general public, in addition to the previously more segregated professionals and patrons, could relate.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As musicians depended more on public support, public concerts became increasingly popular and helped supplement performers' and composers' incomes.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The concerts also helped them to reach a wider audience.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Handel, for example, epitomized this with his highly public musical activities in London.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] He gained considerable fame there with performances of his operas and oratorios.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The music of Haydn and Mozart, with their Viennese Classical styles, are usually regarded as being the most in line with the Enlightenment ideals.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The desire to explore, record, and systematize knowledge had a meaningful impact on music publications.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rousseau's *Dictionnaire de musique* (published 1767 in Geneva and 1768 in Paris) was a leading text in the late 18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This widely available dictionary gave short definitions of words like genius and taste and was clearly influenced by the Enlightenment movement.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Another text influenced by Enlightenment values was Charles Burney's *A General History of Music: From the Earliest Ages to the Present Period* (1776), which was a historical survey and an attempt to rationalize elements in music systematically over time.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Recently, musicologists have shown renewed interest in the ideas and consequences of the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the economy and the middle class expanded, there was an increasing number of amateur musicians.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One manifestation of this involved women, who became more involved with music on a social level.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Women were already engaged in professional roles as singers and increased their presence in the amateur performers' scene, especially with keyboard music.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music publishers began to print music that amateurs could understand and play.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The majority of the works that were published were for keyboard, voice and keyboard, and chamber ensemble.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After these initial genres were popularized, from the mid-century on, amateur groups sang choral music, which then became a new trend for publishers to capitalize on.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increasing study of the fine arts, as well as access to amateur-friendly published works, led to more people becoming interested in reading and discussing music.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music magazines, reviews, and critical works which suited amateurs as well as connoisseurs began to surface.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *philosophes* spent a great deal of energy disseminating their ideas among educated men and women in cosmopolitan cities.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They used many venues, some of them quite new.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Republic of Letters was the sum of a number of Enlightenment ideals: an egalitarian realm governed by knowledge that could act across political boundaries and rival state power.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was a forum that supported "free public examination of questions regarding religion or legislation." Kant considered written communication essential to his conception of the public sphere; once everyone was a part of the "reading public," then society could be said to be enlightened.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The people who participated in the Republic of Letters, such as Diderot and Voltaire, are frequently known today as important Enlightenment figures.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While women were marginalized in the public culture of the Old Regime, the French Revolution destroyed the old cultural and economic restraints of patronage and corporatism (medieval guilds), opening French society to female participation, particularly in the literary sphere.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the established men of letters (*gens de lettres*) had fused with the elites (*les grands*) of French society by the mid-18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was Grub Street literature that was most read by the public during the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] According to Darnton, more importantly the Grub Street hacks inherited the "revolutionary spirit" once displayed by the *philosophes* and paved the way for the French Revolution by desacralizing figures of political, moral, and religious authority in France.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increased consumption of reading materials of all sorts was one of the key features of the "social" Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, demand for reading material extended outside of the realm of the commercial and outside the realm of the upper and middle classes, as evidenced by the bibliothèque bleue.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Literacy rates are difficult to gauge, but in France the rates doubled over the course of the 18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reflecting the decreasing influence of religion, the number of books about science and art published in Paris doubled from 1720 to 1780, while the number of books about religion dropped to just one-tenth of the total.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reading underwent serious changes in the 18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In particular, Rolf Engelsing has argued for the existence of a *reading revolution.* Until 1750, reading was done intensively: people tended to own a small number of books and read them repeatedly, often to small audience.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After 1750, people began to read "extensively," finding as many books as they could, increasingly reading them alone.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is supported by increasing literacy rates, particularly among women.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The vast majority of the reading public could not afford to own a private library, and while most of the state-run "universal libraries" set up in the 17th and 18th centuries were open to the public, they were not the only sources of reading material.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On one end of the spectrum was the *bibliothèque bleue,* a collection of cheaply produced books published in Troyes, France.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Intended for a largely rural and semi-literate audience these books included almanacs, retellings of medieval romances and condensed versions of popular novels, among other things.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While some historians have argued against the Enlightenment's penetration into the lower classes, the *bibliothèque bleue* represents at least a desire to participate in Enlightenment sociability.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Moving up the classes, a variety of institutions offered readers access to material without needing to buy anything.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Libraries that lent out their material for a small price started to appear, and occasionally bookstores would offer a small lending library to their patrons.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffee houses commonly offered books, journals, and sometimes even popular novels to their customers.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Tatler* and *The Spectator,* two influential periodicals sold from 1709 to 1714, were closely associated with coffee house culture in London, being both read and produced in various establishments in the city.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is an example of the triple or even quadruple function of the coffee house: reading material was often obtained, read, discussed, and even produced on the premises.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It is difficult to determine what people actually read during the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, examining the catalogs of private libraries gives an image skewed in favor of the classes wealthy enough to afford libraries and also ignores censored works unlikely to be publicly acknowledged.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For this reason, a study of publishing would be much more fruitful for discerning reading habits.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Across continental Europe, but in France especially, booksellers and publishers had to negotiate censorship laws of varying strictness.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie* narrowly escaped seizure and had to be saved by Malesherbes, the man in charge of the French censor.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, many publishing companies were conveniently located outside France so as to avoid overzealous French censors.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They would smuggle their merchandise across the border, where it would then be transported to clandestine booksellers or small-time peddlers.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The records of clandestine booksellers may give a better representation of what literate Frenchmen might have truly read, since their clandestine nature provided a less restrictive product choice.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In one case, political books were the most popular category, primarily libels and pamphlets.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Readers were more interested in sensationalist stories about criminals and political corruption than they were in political theory itself.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The second most popular category, "general works" (those books "that did not have a dominant motif and that contained something to offend almost everyone in authority"), demonstrated a high demand for generally low-brow subversive literature.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, these works never became part of literary canon and are largely forgotten today as a result.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A healthy, legal publishing industry existed throughout Europe, although established publishers and book sellers occasionally ran afoul of the law.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie*, condemned by both the King and Clement XII, nevertheless found its way into print with the help of the aforementioned Malesherbes and creative use of French censorship law.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, many works were sold without running into any legal trouble at all.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Borrowing records from libraries in England, Germany, and North America indicate that more than 70% of books borrowed were novels.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Less than 1% of the books were of a religious nature, indicating the general trend of declining religiosity.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A genre that greatly rose in importance was that of scientific literature.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Natural history in particular became increasingly popular among the upper classes.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Works of natural history include René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur's *Histoire naturelle des insectes* and Jacques Gautier d'Agoty's *La Myologie complète, ou description de tous les muscles du corps humain* (1746).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Outside Ancien Régime France, natural history was an important part of medicine and industry, encompassing the fields of botany, zoology, meteorology, hydrology, and mineralogy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Students in Enlightenment universities and academies were taught these subjects to prepare them for careers as diverse as medicine and theology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As shown by Matthew Daniel Eddy, natural history in this context was a very middle class pursuit and operated as a fertile trading zone for the interdisciplinary exchange of diverse scientific ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The target audience of natural history was French upper class, evidenced more by the specific discourse of the genre than by the generally high prices of its works.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Naturalists catered to upper class desire for erudition: many texts had an explicit instructive purpose.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, natural history was often a political affair.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In this way, natural history spread many of the scientific developments of the time but also provided a new source of legitimacy for the dominant class.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From this basis, naturalists could then develop their own social ideals based on their scientific works.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first scientific and literary journals were established during the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first journal, the Parisian *Journal des sçavans*, appeared in 1665.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, it was not until 1682 that periodicals began to be more widely produced.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French and Latin were the dominant languages of publication, but there was also a steady demand for material in German and Dutch.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] There was generally low demand for English publications on the continent, which was echoed by England's similar lack of desire for French works.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Languages commanding less of an international market—such as Danish, Spanish, and Portuguese—found journal success more difficult, and a more international language was used instead.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French slowly took over Latin's status as the *lingua franca* of learned circles.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This in turn gave precedence to the publishing industry in Holland, where the vast majority of these French language periodicals were produced.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Jonathan Israel called the journals the most influential cultural innovation of European intellectual culture.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They shifted the attention of the "cultivated public" away from established authorities to novelty and innovation, and instead promoted the Enlightened ideals of toleration and intellectual objectivity.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Being a source of knowledge derived from science and reason, they were an implicit critique of existing notions of universal truth monopolized by monarchies, parliaments, and religious authorities.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They also advanced Christian Enlightenment that upheld "the legitimacy of God-ordained authority"—the Bible—in which there had to be agreement between the biblical and natural theories.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although the existence of dictionaries and encyclopedias spanned into ancient times, the texts changed from defining words in a long running list to far more detailed discussions of those words in 18th-century encyclopedic dictionaries.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The works were part of an Enlightenment movement to systematize knowledge and provide education to a wider audience than the elite.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the 18th century progressed, the content of encyclopedias also changed according to readers' tastes.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Volumes tended to focus more strongly on secular affairs, particularly science and technology, rather than matters of theology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with secular matters, readers also favoured an alphabetical ordering scheme over cumbersome works arranged along thematic lines.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Encyclopedias and dictionaries also became more popular during the Enlightenment as the number of educated consumers who could afford such texts began to multiply.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the latter half of the 18th century, the number of dictionaries and encyclopedias published by decade increased from 63 between 1760 and 1769 to approximately 148 in the decade proceeding the French Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with growth in numbers, dictionaries and encyclopedias also grew in length, often having multiple print runs that sometimes included in supplemented editions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first technical dictionary was drafted by John Harris and entitled *Lexicon Technicum: Or, An Universal English Dictionary of Arts and Sciences.* Harris' book avoids theological and biographical entries and instead concentrates on science and technology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Published in 1704, the *Lexicon Technicum* was the first book to be written in English that took a methodical approach to describing mathematics and commercial arithmetic along with the physical sciences and navigation.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Other technical dictionaries followed Harris' model, including Ephraim Chambers' *Cyclopaedia* (1728), which included five editions and is a substantially larger work than Harris'.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The folio edition of the work even included foldout engravings.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Cyclopaedia* emphasized Newtonian theories, Lockean philosophy and contained thorough examinations of technologies, such as engraving, brewing, and dyeing.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In Germany, practical reference works intended for the uneducated majority became popular in the 18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Marperger Curieuses Natur-, Kunst-, Berg-, Gewerk- und Handlungs-Lexicon* (1712) explained terms that usefully described the trades and scientific and commercial education.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Jablonksi Allgemeines Lexicon* (1721) was better known than the *Handlungs-Lexicon* and underscored technical subjects rather than scientific theory.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, over five columns of text were dedicated to wine while geometry and logic were allocated only twenty-two and seventeen lines, respectively.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first edition of the *Encyclopædia Britannica* (1771) was modelled along the same lines as the German lexicons.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the prime example of reference works that systematized scientific knowledge in the Enlightenment were universal encyclopedias rather than technical dictionaries.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was the goal of universal encyclopedias to record all human knowledge in a comprehensive reference work.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The most well-known of these works is Diderot and d'Alembert's *Encyclopédie, ou dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers.* The work, which began publication in 1751, was composed of 35 volumes and over 71,000 separate entries.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A great number of the entries were dedicated to describing the sciences and crafts in detail and provided intellectuals across Europe with a high-quality survey of human knowledge.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The massive work was arranged according to a "tree of knowledge." The tree reflected the marked division between the arts and sciences, which was largely a result of the rise of empiricism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Both areas of knowledge were united by philosophy, or the trunk of the tree of knowledge.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Enlightenment's desacrilization of religion was pronounced in the tree's design, particularly where theology accounted for a peripheral branch, with black magic as a close neighbour.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the *Encyclopédie* gained popularity, it was published in quarto and octavo editions after 1777.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The quarto and octavo editions were much less expensive than previous editions, making the *Encyclopédie* more accessible to the non-elite.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Robert Darnton estimates that there were approximately 25,000 copies of the *Encyclopédie* in circulation throughout France and Europe before the French Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The extensive yet affordable encyclopedia came to represent the transmission of Enlightenment and scientific education to an expanding audience.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most important developments that the Enlightenment era brought to the discipline of science was its popularization.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] An increasingly literate population seeking knowledge and education in both the arts and the sciences drove the expansion of print culture and the dissemination of scientific learning.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The new literate population was precipitated by a high rise in the availability of food; this enabled many people to rise out of poverty, and instead of paying more for food, they had money for education.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More formal works included explanations of scientific theories for individuals lacking the educational background to comprehend the original scientific text.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Newton's celebrated *Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica* was published in Latin and remained inaccessible to readers without education in the classics until Enlightenment writers began to translate and analyze the text in the vernacular.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first significant work that expressed scientific theory and knowledge expressly for the laity, in the vernacular and with the entertainment of readers in mind, was Bernard de Fontenelle's *Conversations on the Plurality of Worlds* (1686).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The book was produced specifically for women with an interest in scientific writing and inspired a variety of similar works.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These popular works were written in a discursive style, which was laid out much more clearly for the reader than the complicated articles, treatises, and books published by the academies and scientists.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Writing for a growing female audience, Francesco Algarotti published *Il Newtonianism per le dame*, which was a tremendously popular work and was translated from Italian into English by Elizabeth Carter.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A similar introduction to Newtonianism for women was produced by Henry Pemberton.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] His *A View of Sir Isaac Newton's Philosophy* was published by subscription.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Extant records of subscribers show that women from a wide range of social standings purchased the book, indicating the growing number of scientifically inclined female readers among the middling class.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, women also began producing popular scientific works.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Sarah Trimmer wrote a successful natural history textbook for children titled *The Easy Introduction to the Knowledge of Nature* (1782), which was published for many years in eleven editions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Most work on the Enlightenment emphasizes the ideals discussed by intellectuals, rather than the actual state of education at the time.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leading educational theorists like England's John Locke and Switzerland's Jean Jacques Rousseau both emphasized the importance of shaping young minds early.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] By the late Enlightenment, there was a rising demand for a more universal approach to education, particularly after the American Revolution and the French Revolution.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The predominant educational psychology from the 1750s onward, especially in northern European countries, was associationism: the notion that the mind associates or dissociates ideas through repeated routines.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Children were taught to memorize facts through oral and graphic methods that originated during the Renaissance.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Many of the leading universities associated with Enlightenment progressive principles were located in northern Europe, with the most renowned being the universities of Leiden, Göttingen, Halle, Montpellier, Uppsala, and Edinburgh.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These universities, especially Edinburgh, produced professors whose ideas had a significant impact on Britain's North American colonies and later the American Republic.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Within the natural sciences, Edinburgh's medical school also led the way in chemistry, anatomy, and pharmacology.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In other parts of Europe, the universities and schools of France and most of Europe were bastions of traditionalism and were not hospitable to the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the major exception was the medical university at Montpellier.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The history of Academies in France during the Enlightenment begins with the Academy of Science, founded in 1666 in Paris.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was closely tied to the French state, acting as an extension of a government seriously lacking in scientists.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It helped promote and organize new disciplines and it trained new scientists.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It also contributed to the enhancement of scientists' social status, considering them to be the "most useful of all citizens." Academies demonstrate the rising interest in science along with its increasing secularization, as evidenced by the small number of clerics who were members (13%).
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of the French academies in the public sphere cannot be attributed to their membership, as although the majority of their members were bourgeois, the exclusive institution was only open to elite Parisian scholars.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They perceived themselves as "interpreters of the sciences for the people." For example, it was with this in mind that academicians took it upon themselves to disprove the popular pseudo-science of mesmerism.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The strongest contribution of the French Academies to the public sphere comes from the *concours académiques* (roughly translated as "academic contests") they sponsored throughout France.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These academic contests were perhaps the most public of any institution during the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The practice of contests dated back to the Middle Ages and was revived in the mid-17th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The subject matter had previously been generally religious and/or monarchical, featuring essays, poetry, and painting.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More importantly, the contests were open to all, and the enforced anonymity of each submission guaranteed that neither gender nor social rank would determine the judging.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, although the "vast majority" of participants belonged to the wealthier strata of society ("the liberal arts, the clergy, the judiciary and the medical profession"), there were some cases of the popular classes submitting essays and even winning.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similarly, a significant number of women participated—and won—the competitions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Of a total of 2,300 prize competitions offered in France, women won 49—perhaps a small number by modern standards but very significant in an age in which very few women had any academic training.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, the majority of the winning entries were for poetry competitions, a genre commonly stressed in women's education.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In England, the Royal Society of London played a significant role in the public sphere and the spread of Enlightenment ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was founded by a group of independent scientists and given a royal charter in 1662.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The society played a large role in spreading Robert Boyle's experimental philosophy around Europe and acted as a clearinghouse for intellectual correspondence and exchange.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Boyle was "a founder of the experimental world in which scientists now live and operate" and his method based knowledge on experimentation, which had to be witnessed to provide proper empirical legitimacy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is where the Royal Society came into play: witnessing had to be a "collective act" and the Royal Society's assembly rooms were ideal locations for relatively public demonstrations.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Salons were places where *philosophes* were reunited and discussed old, actual, or new ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This led to salons being the birthplace of intellectual and enlightened ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were especially important to the spread of knowledge during the Enlightenment because they created a unique environment in which people from many different walks of life gathered and shared ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They were frequently criticized by nobles who feared the possibility of an environment in which class and its accompanying titles and privileges were disregarded.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Such an environment was especially intimidating to monarchs who derived much of their power from the disparity between classes of people.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] If the different classes joined together under the influence of Enlightenment thinking, they might recognize the all-encompassing oppression and abuses of their monarchs and because of the numbers of their members might be able to successfully revolt.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Monarchs also resented the idea of their subjects convening as one to discuss political matters, especially matters of foreign affairs.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rulers thought political affairs were their business only, a result of their divine right to rule.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeeshops became homes away from home for many who sought to engage in discourse with their neighbors and discuss intriguing and thought-provoking matters, from philosophy to politics.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were essential to the Enlightenment, for they were centers of free-thinking and self-discovery.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although many coffeehouse patrons were scholars, many were not.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses attracted a diverse set of people, including the educated wealthy and bourgeois as well as the lower classes.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Patrons, being doctors, lawyers, merchants, represented almost all classes, so the coffeeshop environment sparked fear in those who wanted to preserve class distinction.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most popular critiques of the coffeehouse said that it "allowed promiscuous association among people from different rungs of the social ladder, from the artisan to the aristocrat" and was therefore compared to Noah's Ark, receiving all types of animals, clean and unclean.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This unique culture served as a catalyst for journalism, when Joseph Addison and Richard Steele recognized its potential as an audience.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Together, Steele and Addison published *The Spectator (1711)*, a daily publication which aimed, through fictional narrator Mr.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Spectator, to both entertain and provoke discussion on serious philosophical matters.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first English coffeehouse opened in Oxford in 1650.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Brian Cowan said that Oxford coffeehouses developed into "penny universities," offering a locus of learning that was less formal than at structured institutions.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These penny universities occupied a significant position in Oxford academic life, as they were frequented by those consequently referred to as the *virtuosi,* who conducted their research on some of the premises.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was established in Paris in 1686, and by the 1720s there were around 400 cafés in the city.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope in particular became a center of Enlightenment, welcoming such celebrities as Voltaire and Rousseau.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was where Diderot and D'Alembert decided to create the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The cafés were one of the various "nerve centers" for *bruits publics,* public noise or rumour.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These *bruits* were allegedly a much better source of information than were the actual newspapers available at the time.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies are an example of the public sphere during the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the late 1770s, popular debating societies began to move into more "genteel" rooms, a change which helped establish a new standard of sociability.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The backdrop to these developments was "an explosion of interest in the theory and practice of public elocution." The debating societies were commercial enterprises that responded to this demand, sometimes very successfully.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Some societies welcomed from 800 to 1,200 spectators per night.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies discussed an extremely wide range of topics.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In addition to debates on religion, societies discussed issues such as politics and the role of women.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the critical subject matter of these debates did not necessarily translate into opposition to the government; the results of the debate quite frequently upheld the *status quo*.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From a historical standpoint, one of the most important features of the debating society was their openness to the public, as women attended and even participated in almost every debating society, which were likewise open to all classes providing they could pay the entrance fee.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Once inside, spectators were able to participate in a largely egalitarian form of sociability that helped spread Enlightenment ideas.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historians have debated the extent to which the secret network of Freemasonry was a main factor in the Enlightenment.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leaders of the Enlightenment included Freemasons such as Diderot, Montesquieu, Voltaire, Lessing, Pope, Horace Walpole, Robert Walpole, Mozart, Goethe, Frederick the Great, Benjamin Franklin and George Washington.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Norman Davies said Freemasonry was a powerful force on behalf of liberalism in Europe from about 1700 to the twentieth century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It expanded during the Enlightenment, reaching practically every country in Europe.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was especially attractive to powerful aristocrats and politicians as well as intellectuals, artists, and political activists.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, Freemasons comprised an international network of like-minded men, often meeting in secret in ritualistic programs at their lodges.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They promoted the ideals of the Enlightenment and helped diffuse these values across Britain, France, and other places.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry as a systematic creed with its own myths, values, and rituals originated in Scotland c.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] 1600 and spread to England and then across the Continent in the 18th century.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry was particularly prevalent in France—by 1789, there were perhaps as many as 100,000 French Masons, making Freemasonry the most popular of all Enlightenment associations.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Freemasons displayed a passion for secrecy and created new degrees and ceremonies.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similar societies, partially imitating Freemasonry, emerged in France, Germany, Sweden, and Russia.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One example was the Illuminati, founded in Bavaria in 1776, which was copied after the Freemasons, but was never part of the movement.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The name itself translates to "enlightened," chosen to reflect their original intent to promote the values of the movement.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Illuminati was an overtly political group, which most Masonic lodges decidedly were not.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Masonic lodges created a private model for public affairs.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They "reconstituted the polity and established a constitutional form of self-government, complete with constitutions and laws, elections, and representatives." In other words, the micro-society set up within the lodges constituted a normative model for society as a whole.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This was especially true on the continent: when the first lodges began to appear in the 1730s, their embodiment of British values was often seen as threatening by state authorities.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the Parisian lodge that met in the mid 1720s was composed of English Jacobite exiles.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Furthermore, freemasons across Europe explicitly linked themselves to the Enlightenment as a whole.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, in French lodges the line "As the means to be enlightened I search for the enlightened" was a part of their initiation rites.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] British lodges assigned themselves the duty to "initiate the unenlightened." This did not necessarily link lodges to the irreligious, but neither did this exclude them from the occasional heresy.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In fact, many lodges praised the Grand Architect, the masonic terminology for the deistic divine being who created a scientifically ordered universe.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Diderot discusses the link between Freemason ideals and the enlightenment in D'Alembert's Dream, exploring masonry as a way of spreading enlightenment beliefs.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historian Margaret Jacob stresses the importance of the Masons in indirectly inspiring enlightened political thought.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On the negative side, Daniel Roche contests claims that Masonry promoted egalitarianism and he argues the lodges only attracted men of similar social backgrounds.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of noble women in the French "lodges of adoption" that formed in the 1780s was largely due to the close ties shared between these lodges and aristocratic society.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The major opponent of Freemasonry was the Catholic Church so in countries with a large Catholic element, such as France, Italy, Spain, and Mexico, much of the ferocity of the political battles involve the confrontation between what Davies calls the reactionary Church and enlightened Freemasonry.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Even in France, Masons did not act as a group.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] American historians, while noting that Benjamin Franklin and George Washington were indeed active Masons, have downplayed the importance of Freemasonry in causing the American Revolution because the Masonic order was non-political and included both Patriots and their enemy the Loyalists.
[src:hospital/age-of-enlightenment-p03] At the same time, the classical art of Greece and Rome became interesting to people again, since archaeological teams discovered Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The idea of AIIMS arose in 1946, after a recommendation by the Health Survey of the Government of India.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] From then to the establishment and development of AIIMS (New Delhi) over the ensuing years, several illustrious individuals played their part in bringing the idea to fruition.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Originally proposed by the then Prime Minister of India Jawaharlal Nehru for establishment in Calcutta, it was established in New Delhi following the refusal of Chief Minister of West Bengal Bidhan Chandra Roy.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The foundation stone of AIIMS Delhi was laid in 1952.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] On 18 February 1956, the then Minister of Health, Rajkumari Amrit Kaur, introduced a new bill in the Lok Sabha, that would eventually become the AIIMS Act.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The old and new main OPD blocks at AIIMS, New Delhi are named after her.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] When the bill was adopted in May 1956, it became the All India Institute of Medical Sciences Act, 1956.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The whole campus is spread over an area of 213.12 acres.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS, New Delhi's main campus is located in Ansari Nagar in Delhi.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It is adjacent to the South Extension-II market and lies on both sides of the Sri Aurobindo Marg, southwards to the AIIMS Roundabout flyover crossing.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] **West Campus** – It comprises mainly staff quarters and residences.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] **JPNA Trauma Center** – It is exclusively designated for Emergency services.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] In June 2018, a tunnel and ramp road link between the east campus and JPNA Trauma Center Campus was also opened.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] This link route is very useful in fast transferring of critical patients across the two Campuses.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Beside JPNA Trauma Center, new 100 Bed Plastic and Burns Surgical Unit Hospital is also running, it will also comprise a Skin Bank for Burns Injuries.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] **Masjid Moth Campus** – This site contains new Post-Graduate and Resident Doctor's apartments.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Underground parking block is also situated here.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Upcoming New Rajkumari Amrit Kaur OPD Block, Mother and Child Block, Surgical Block and Geriatric Block (National Centre for Ageing) are also functional here.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] **Ayurvigyan Nagar Campus** – It is too for faculty and staff's residential accommodations.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Across AIIMS is Safdarjung Hospital and associated Vardhman Mahavir Medical College (of Guru Gobind Singh Indraprastha University).
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Also, adjacently lies the headquarters of Indian Council of Medical Research, the body that coordinates and funds medical research in India.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] In vicinity, also lies National Medical Library, run by the Directorate-General of Health Services of the Government of India.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It has a vast collection of scientific and medical journals that can be accessed by researchers.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The second campus of All India Institute of Medical Sciences (AIIMS-II), spread over 330 acres (1.335 square kilometres) of land was visualized during the period of Prof.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Tirath Das Dogra as Director AIIMS Delhi and Anbumani Ramadoss (President, AIIMS), Minister of Health and Family welfare union of India in 2009 at Bhadsha village [also spelled Badsa] in Haryana's Jhajjar district.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS-II was thought to be developed as the largest medical Education centre for super-specialities in the world to meet the enormous need of super-specialists in various field in India.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The 330 acres of land was donated by the then Chief Minister Bhupinder Singh Hooda, of Haryana to Anbumani Ramadoss, in presence of Director AIIMS Tirath Das Dogra, in a big public function on 28 February 2009 at the proposed site.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The National Cancer Institute is first to come up, next is the National Cardiovascular centre as a joint venture between Govt of Haryana and Union health ministry in a series of future developments as envisaged.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The next under the plan is a unique collaborative centre between IITD-Jhajjar campus located adjacent to the AIIMS (New Delhi)'s Jhajjar Extension.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] They jointly are to set up a "biomedical research park", running joint PhD/research programmes managed through the *Foundation for Innovation and Technology Transfer* (FITT).
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It became operational on 18 December 2018 including OPD, lab and 250-bed hospital which will be expanded to 710 beds by December 2019.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Rath former Head of Department of Oncology at AIIMS (New Delhi).
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] National Heart Institute (India) is also being established here.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] A heliport is being developed here in January 2019 for the Air Ambulance to serve emergency patients from remote areas.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Ballabhgarh, established in 1965, is an extension campus of AIIMS in Ballabhgarh city of Faridabad district in Haryana.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] This rural field practice OPD campus was set up in collaboration with Government of Haryana as "Comprehensive Rural Health Services Project" – "Ballabgarh Health and Demographic Surveillance System".
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] In 1961 Rural Field Practice was established at AIIMS (New Delhi) with the help of Rockefeller Foundation.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] An intensive field practice area, the National Drug Dependence Treatment Centre is an extension campus of AIIMS (New Delhi) in Ghaziabad city of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The Drug Dependence Treatment Centre, AIIMS was established in the year 1988 and was functional in New Delhi.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] In 2003 it was upgraded as a National Centre (National Drug Dependence Treatment Centre) and is fully operational from its new premises in Ghaziabad, Delhi-NCR since April 2003.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] NDDTC has been established as the apex centre for treatment of drugs and substance abuse disorders in the country.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It provides a state of art model for de-addiction treatments.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] This centre has full range of specialists and facilities.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The NDDTC is situated on 10 acre beautiful campus.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] PhD Programme in the area of Addiction Psychiatry and DM (Addiction Psychiatry) Programme started since year 2012 and 2015 respectively.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The Ex-Chief of the centre was a member of the International Narcotics Control Board (INCB), a monitoring body under the United Nations.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] In February 2019 The Union Cabinet chaired by Prime Minister of India has given 'in principle' approval to the Implementation of Master Plan to convert All India Institute of Medical Sciences (AIIMS), New Delhi into a world class Medical University.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The visualization at the time of institute's construction (in 1950s) was for a limited number of patients.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The medical institute was established as a tertiary-care centre, but now it has turned into a primary care centre.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Over time, the requirement has increased manifold.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The upcoming master plan will now have a vision for the next decade.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The project would provide highly specialized state-of-the-art healthcare to the patients and an integrated 'One Campus' answer to all the investigative, physiotherapeutic, operative, rehabilitative and vocational needs of the patients.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It would ensure smart mobility and accessibility for the patients and become an apex tertiary care centre for advancement of research, clinical applications and management of patients.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] By 2024, AIIMS (New Delhi) will add around 3,000 more beds to its existing strength of 2,478 beds.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] So there will be a facility of approximately 5,500 beds in service by then.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] A move that will come as a relief for thousands of patients who visit the hospital every day as presently the hospital sees a daily footfall of almost 15,000 patients and their attendants.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It also aims to strengthen patient-care services and residential facilities for faculty members and staff.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Officials said the estimated cost of executing the master plan is around ₹10,345 crore, including ₹1,000 crore for hiring manpower.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The project will be completed in two phases; while Phase 1 will be completed in 46 months, the second phase will be finalized in 70 months.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] As per the plan, a convention centre, a guesthouse with 40 rooms, a hostel with more than 4,500 rooms and 500 residential units with allied car parking will be set up.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] As there is no scope of further expansion with the limited availability of land, residential facilities stretching from Trauma Centre campus, West Campus (Ansari Nagar) to East Campus (Ansari Nagar) and Ayurvigyan Nagar Campus will be relocated.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] This will free up space in the main campus and allow to expand vertically.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] With senior faculty members raising issues of shortage of labs and operation theaters in the institute, the administration hopes the upcoming project will look into that concern.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] This new plan will also create scope for research projects, which have been pending due to space constraints.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS (New Delhi) was originally established as a super-specialty tertiary care centre with primary emphasis on research and specialized training facilities.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] MBBS is the basic medical course at bachelor's degree level.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] This is followed by master's degree level specialisation in general surgery, general medicine, pediatrics and other fields.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Superspecialties are those healthcare fields whose practitioners need specialised certification after completing their postgraduation, examples being cardiothoracic and vascular surgery, rheumatology, neurology, and pediatric neurology.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] There are at least 45 superspecialties at AIIMS (New Delhi) at higher master's degree level.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS also offers MSc and PhD level research courses.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] There are about forty-two specialty post-graduate courses conducted at AIIMS (New Delhi).
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The entry is through a nationwide competitive examination, INI-CET, held every six months.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Each year nearly 50 thousand medical graduates and 25 thousand dental graduates across the country compete for the limited number of positions, approximately <1% of the candidates are admitted through the process.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS publishes *The National Medical Journal of India*.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] As per the latest official notification released by the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare, AIIMS, JIPMER -Puducherry, PGI -Chandigarh & all INIs (Institutes of National Importance) were directed not to conduct any Undergraduate entrance exams from 2020 onwards.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Government has said that from 2020 session onwards, all such undergraduate admissions would be taken up only through a single national level examination NEET-UG conducted by NTA (National Testing Agency).
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] And that was something really crucial for the main objectives for which AIIMS (New Delhi) was established, which are cutting-edge research, medical innovations and to demonstrate high standards of medical education to all medical colleges and allied institutions in India.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS was the first Indian medical center to perform a successful cardiac transplant.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The surgery was performed by P Venugopal, the ex-director of AIIMS, in 1994.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS is an advanced center of stem cell therapy in India, especially cardiac and neurological.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It holds a reputation of being a pioneer in stem cell injection.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The first in-vitro fertilization facility in the public sector was set up at AIIMS, New Delhi in February 2008.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS New Delhi was ranked 204th in the world and first in South Asia in the category of Life Sciences and Medicine by QS WUR in 2022.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The institute was also featured in the World's Best Hospitals 2020 – Top 100 by Newsweek.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] AIIMS New Delhi was ranked first among medical colleges in India by the National Institutional Ranking Framework in 2024.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] It was also ranked first in India by *India Today* in 2024 and first among government colleges by Outlook India in 2024.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Subsequently, on many investigations done by Chaturvedi, CBI registered cases and recommended action against Vineet Chawdhry.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] As per *India Today* investigative report of June 2017, J P Nadda, Union Health Minister was found to have hushed up investigation into what the report termed as 7000 crore scam, detailing CBI report and scathing reports of Parliamentary Committee.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] On 23 November 2022, servers of AIIMS New Delhi were hacked by a ransomware attack after an employee opened a phishing mail.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The hackers have encrypted the servers and were demanding ₹200 crores in cryptocurrency, however Delhi Police did not confirm reports of ransom demand.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Patient care services in emergency, outpatient, inpatient and laboratory wings were forced to be managed manually.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Investigation has confirmed that five main servers were targeted by Chinese hackers based out of Hong Kong.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] Delhi Police, Representatives of Ministry of Home Affairs, Indian Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT-IN), Centre for Development of Advanced Computing (C-DAC) and National Informatics Centre (NIC) are investigating the ransomware attack.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] A case of extortion and cyber terrorism was registered by the Intelligence Fusion and Strategic Operations (IFSO) unit of the Delhi Police on 25 November.
[src:hospital/aiims-new-delhi] The online registration of new patients visiting the OPD at the AIIMS resumed on 6 December 2022 while online OPD booking system was restored by 2nd week of December 2022.
[src:hospital/com] The domain **com** is a top-level domain (TLD) in the Domain Name System (DNS) of the Internet.
[src:hospital/com] Created in the first group of Internet domains in March of 1985, it is short for *commercial*, as it was originally intended for subdomains for commercial organizations.
[src:hospital/com] Later, the domain opened for general purposes.
[src:hospital/com] The domain was originally administered by the United States Department of Defense, but is today operated by Verisign, and remains under ultimate jurisdiction of U.S. law.
[src:hospital/com] The *.com* domain is more commonly used than the more specific *.us* by American businesses and enterprises.
[src:hospital/com] Verisign registrations in the .com domain are processed via registrars accredited by ICANN.
[src:hospital/com] The registry accepts internationalized domain names.
[src:hospital/com] The domain was one of the original TLDs of the Internet when the Domain Name System was implemented in January 1985, the others being edu, gov, mil, net, org, and int.
[src:hospital/com] It has grown into the largest top-level domain, and has lent its name to the dot-com bubble, the era of the late 1990s during which excessive speculation in Internet-related concepts and companies led to rapid growth in the use and adoption of the Internet.
[src:hospital/com] The domain *com* was one of the first set of top-level domains when the Domain Name System was first implemented for the Internet on January 1, 1985.
[src:hospital/com] Department of Defense, but the department contracted the domain maintenance to SRI International.
[src:hospital/com] SRI created DDN-NIC, also known as SRI-NIC, or simply *the NIC* (Network Information Center), then accessible online with the domain name nic.ddn.mil.
[src:hospital/com] Beginning October 1, 1991, an operations contract was awarded to Government Systems Inc.
[src:hospital/com] (GSI), which sub-contracted it to Network Solutions Inc.
[src:hospital/com] On January 1, 1993, the National Science Foundation assumed responsibility of maintenance, as com was primarily being used for non-defense interests.
[src:hospital/com] The NSF contracted operation to Network Solutions (NSI).
[src:hospital/com] In 1995, the NSF authorized NSI to begin charging registrants an annual fee for the first time since the domain's inception.
[src:hospital/com] Initially, the fee was US$50 (equivalent to $106 in 2025) per year, with US$35 going to NSI, and US$15 going to a government fund.
[src:hospital/com] New registrations had to pay for the first two years, making the new-domain registration fee US$100.
[src:hospital/com] In 1997, the United States Department of Commerce assumed authority over these first seven generic TLDs.
[src:hospital/com] It is currently operated by Verisign, which had acquired Network Solutions.
[src:hospital/com] Verisign later spun off Network Solutions' non-registry functions into a separate company that continues as a registrar.
[src:hospital/com] In the English language, the domain is often spelled with a leading period and commonly pronounced as *dot-com*, and has entered common parlance this way.
[src:hospital/com] Although com domains were initially intended to designate commercial entities, the domain has had no restrictions for eligible registrants since the mid-1990s.
[src:hospital/com] With the commercialization and popularization of the Internet, the domain was opened to the public and quickly became the most common top-level domain for websites, email, and networking.
[src:hospital/com] Many companies that flourished in the period from 1997 to 2001—the time known as the "dot-com bubble"—incorporated the label *com* into company names; these became known as dot-coms or dot-com companies.
[src:hospital/com] The introduction of domain *biz* in 2001, which was aimed at companies that failed to register a suitable com-domain name, intended to make customers realize that they had arrived at a legitimate business website, although it did not achieve widespread use.
[src:hospital/com] Many non-commercial sites and networks use com names to benefit from the perceived recognizability of a com domain.
[src:hospital/com] However, the registration statistics show varying popularity over the years.
[src:hospital/com] In December 2011, Verisign reported that approximately 100 million com domains were registered.
[src:hospital/com] According to the Domain Name Industry Brief published in March 2020, which publishes every quarter, com domain registration totaled 145.4 million.
[src:hospital/com] As of March 2009, Verisign reported that 926 accredited registrars serve the domain.
[src:hospital/com] Department of Commerce approved the renewal of the com Registry Agreement between Verisign, Inc., and ICANN.
[src:hospital/com] Through this agreement, Verisign managed the com registry until November 30, 2018.
[src:hospital/com] The following are the 100 oldest still-existing registered *com* domains.
[src:hospital/com] After the success of the .com domain, CentralNic registered multiple TLD Extensions under the format: `.Country.Com`.
[src:hospital/hospital] A **hospital** is a healthcare institution providing patient treatment with specialized medical science and auxiliary healthcare staff and medical equipment.
[src:hospital/hospital] The best-known type of hospital is the **general hospital**, which typically has an emergency department to treat urgent health problems ranging from fire and accident victims to a sudden illness.
[src:hospital/hospital] A **district hospital** typically is the major health care facility in its region, with many beds for intensive care and additional beds for patients who need long-term care.
[src:hospital/hospital] Specialized hospitals include trauma centers, rehabilitation hospitals, children's hospitals, geriatric hospitals, and hospitals for specific medical needs, such as psychiatric hospitals for psychiatric treatment and other disease-specific categories.
[src:hospital/hospital] Specialized hospitals can help reduce health care costs compared to general hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals are classified as general, specialty, or government depending on the sources of income received.
[src:hospital/hospital] A teaching hospital campus combines patient care with teaching to health science students, auxiliary healthcare students, and qualified medical graduates completing their postgraduate residencies before licensure to practice.
[src:hospital/hospital] A health science facility smaller than a hospital is generally called a clinic.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals have a range of departments (e.g. surgery and urgent care) and specialist units such as cardiology.
[src:hospital/hospital] Some hospitals have outpatient departments and some have chronic treatment units.
[src:hospital/hospital] Common support units include a pharmacy, pathology, and radiology.
[src:hospital/hospital] Facilities that combine many health care functions, including general or specialized patient care, teaching, research, and so on, may use the term medical center.
[src:hospital/hospital] This term can also refer to an office complex with various unaffiliated health services or any kind of clinic or hospital.
[src:hospital/hospital] A large hospital or medical center also often serves as the administrative headquarters of a larger health system which may have multiple sites.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals are typically funded by public funding, health organizations (for-profit or nonprofit), health insurance companies, or charities, including direct charitable donations.
[src:hospital/hospital] Historically, hospitals were often founded and funded by Christian religious orders, or by charitable individuals and leaders.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals are currently staffed by professional physicians, surgeons, nurses, and allied health professionals.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the past, however, this work was usually performed by the members of founding religious orders or by volunteers.
[src:hospital/hospital] However, there are various Catholic religious orders, such as the Alexians and the Bon Secours Sisters that still focus on hospital ministry in the late 1990s, as well as several other Christian denominations, including the Evangelical-Lutherans and Methodists, which run hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] Deaconesses have played a prominent role in healthcare.
[src:hospital/hospital] In accordance with the original meaning of the word, hospitals were original "places of hospitality", and this meaning is still preserved in the names of some institutions such as the Royal Hospital Chelsea, established in 1681 as a retirement and nursing home for veteran soldiers.
[src:hospital/hospital] During the Middle Ages, hospitals served different functions from modern institutions in that they were almshouses for the poor, hostels for pilgrims, or hospital schools.
[src:hospital/hospital] The word "hospital" comes from the Latin *hospes*, signifying a stranger or foreigner, hence a guest.
[src:hospital/hospital] Another noun derived from this, *hospitium* came to signify hospitality, that is the relation between guest and shelterer, hospitality, friendliness, and hospitable reception.
[src:hospital/hospital] By metonymy, the Latin word then came to mean a guest-chamber, guest's lodging, an inn.
[src:hospital/hospital] *Hospes* is thus the root for the English words *host* (where the *p* was dropped for convenience of pronunciation) *hospitality*, *hospice*, *hostel,* and *hotel*.
[src:hospital/hospital] The latter modern word derives from Latin via the Old French romance word *hostel*, which developed a silent *s*, which letter was eventually removed from the word, the loss of which is signified by a circumflex in the modern French word *hôtel*.
[src:hospital/hospital] The German word *Spital* shares similar roots.
[src:hospital/hospital] Some patients go to a hospital just for diagnosis, treatment, or therapy and then leave ("outpatients") without staying overnight; while others are "admitted" and stay overnight or for several days or weeks or months ("inpatients").
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals are usually distinguished from other types of medical facilities by their ability to admit and care for inpatients whilst the others, which are smaller, are often described as clinics.
[src:hospital/hospital] The best-known type of hospital is the general hospital, also known as an acute-care hospital.
[src:hospital/hospital] These facilities handle many kinds of disease and injury, and normally have an emergency department (sometimes known as "accident & emergency") or trauma center to deal with immediate and urgent threats to health.
[src:hospital/hospital] Larger cities may have several hospitals of varying sizes and facilities.
[src:hospital/hospital] Some hospitals, especially in the United States and Canada, have their own ambulance service.
[src:hospital/hospital] A district hospital typically is the major health care facility in its region, with large numbers of beds for intensive care, critical care, and long-term care.
[src:hospital/hospital] In California, "district hospital" refers specifically to a class of healthcare facility created shortly after World War II to address a shortage of hospital beds in many local communities.
[src:hospital/hospital] Even today, district hospitals are the sole public hospitals in 19 of California's counties, and are the sole locally accessible hospital within nine additional counties in which one or more other hospitals are present at a substantial distance from a local community.
[src:hospital/hospital] Twenty-eight of California's rural hospitals and 20 of its critical-access hospitals are district hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] They are formed by local municipalities, have boards that are individually elected by their local communities, and exist to serve local needs.
[src:hospital/hospital] They are a particularly important provider of healthcare to uninsured patients and patients with Medi-Cal (which is California's Medicaid program, serving low-income persons, some senior citizens, persons with disabilities, children in foster care, and pregnant women).
[src:hospital/hospital] In 2012, district hospitals provided $54 million in uncompensated care in California.
[src:hospital/hospital] A specialty hospital is primarily and exclusively dedicated to one or a few related medical specialties.
[src:hospital/hospital] In Germany, specialised hospitals are called *Fachkrankenhaus*; an example is Fachkrankenhaus Coswig (thoracic surgery).
[src:hospital/hospital] In India, specialty hospitals are known as *super-specialty hospitals* and are distinguished from multispecialty hospitals which are composed of several specialties.
[src:hospital/hospital] Specialised hospitals can help reduce health care costs compared to general hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] For example, Narayana Health's cardiac unit in Bangalore specialises in cardiac surgery and allows for a significantly greater number of patients.
[src:hospital/hospital] It has 3,000 beds and performs 3,000 paediatric cardiac operations annually, the largest number in the world for such a facility.
[src:hospital/hospital] Surgeons are paid on a fixed salary instead of per operation, thus when the number of procedures increases, the hospital is able to take advantage of economies of scale and reduce its cost per procedure.
[src:hospital/hospital] Each specialist may also become more efficient by working on one procedure like a production line.
[src:hospital/hospital] A teaching hospital delivers healthcare to patients as well as training to prospective medical professionals such as medical students and student nurses.
[src:hospital/hospital] It may be linked to a medical school or nursing school, and may be involved in medical research.
[src:hospital/hospital] Students may also observe clinical work in the hospital.
[src:hospital/hospital] Clinics generally provide only outpatient services, but some may have a few inpatient beds and a limited range of services that may otherwise be found in typical hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] A hospital contains one or more wards that house hospital beds for inpatients.
[src:hospital/hospital] It may also have acute services such as an emergency department, operating theatre, and intensive care unit, as well as a range of medical specialty departments.
[src:hospital/hospital] A well-equipped hospital may be classified as a trauma center.
[src:hospital/hospital] They may also have other services such as a hospital pharmacy, radiology, pathology, and medical laboratories.
[src:hospital/hospital] Some hospitals have outpatient departments such as behavioral health services, dentistry, and rehabilitation services.
[src:hospital/hospital] Freestanding emergency departments are often associated with a hospital, but are located away from the hospital with the intention of providing greater emergency service coverage to a region.
[src:hospital/hospital] A hospital may also have a department of nursing, headed by a chief nursing officer or director of nursing.
[src:hospital/hospital] This department is responsible for the administration of professional nursing practice, research, and policy for the hospital.
[src:hospital/hospital] Many units have both a nursing and a medical director that serve as administrators for their respective disciplines within that unit.
[src:hospital/hospital] For example, within an intensive care nursery, a medical director is responsible for physicians and medical care, while the nursing manager is responsible for all the nurses and nursing care.
[src:hospital/hospital] Support units may include a medical records department, release of information department, technical support, clinical engineering, facilities management, plant operations, dining services, and security departments.
[src:hospital/hospital] The COVID-19 pandemic stimulated the development of virtual wards across the British NHS.
[src:hospital/hospital] Patients are managed at home, monitoring their own oxygen levels using an oxygen saturation probe if necessary and supported by telephone.
[src:hospital/hospital] West Hertfordshire Hospitals NHS Trust managed around 1200 patients at home between March and June 2020 and planned to continue the system after COVID-19, initially for respiratory patients.
[src:hospital/hospital] Mersey Care NHS Foundation Trust started a COVID Oximetry@Home service in April 2020.
[src:hospital/hospital] This enables them to monitor more than 5000 patients a day in their own homes.
[src:hospital/hospital] The technology allows nurses, carers, or patients to record and monitor vital signs such as blood oxygen levels.
[src:hospital/hospital] In early India, Fa Xian, a Chinese Buddhist monk who travelled across India c.
[src:hospital/hospital] AD 400, recorded examples of healing institutions.
[src:hospital/hospital] According to the *Mahavamsa*, the ancient chronicle of Sinhalese royalty, written in the sixth century AD, King Pandukabhaya of Sri Lanka (r.
[src:hospital/hospital] 437–367 BC) had lying-in-homes and hospitals (Sivikasotthi-Sala).
[src:hospital/hospital] A hospital and medical training center also existed at Gundeshapur, a major city in southwest of the Sassanid Persian Empire founded in AD 271 by Shapur I.
[src:hospital/hospital] In ancient Greece, temples dedicated to the healer-god Asclepius, known as Asclepeion functioned as centers of medical advice, prognosis, and healing.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Asclepeia spread to the Roman Empire.
[src:hospital/hospital] While public healthcare was non-existent in the Roman Empire, military hospitals called *valetudinaria* did exist stationed in military barracks and would serve the soldiers and slaves within the fort.
[src:hospital/hospital] Evidence exists that some civilian hospitals, while unavailable to the Roman population, were occasionally privately built in extremely wealthy Roman households located in the countryside for that family, although this practice seems to have ended in 80 AD.
[src:hospital/hospital] The declaration of Christianity as an accepted religion in the Roman Empire drove an expansion of the provision of care.
[src:hospital/hospital] Following the First Council of Nicaea in AD 325 construction of a hospital in every cathedral town was begun, including among the earliest hospitals by Saint Sampson in Constantinople and by Basil, bishop of Caesarea in modern-day Turkey.
[src:hospital/hospital] By the twelfth century, Constantinople had two well-organised hospitals, staffed by doctors who were both male and female.
[src:hospital/hospital] Facilities included systematic treatment procedures and specialised wards for various diseases.
[src:hospital/hospital] The earliest general hospital in the Islamic world was built in 805 in Baghdad by Harun Al-Rashid.
[src:hospital/hospital] By the 10th century, Baghdad had five more hospitals, while Damascus had six hospitals by the 15th century, and Córdoba alone had 50 major hospitals, many exclusively for the military, by the end of the 15th century.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Islamic bimaristan served as a center of medical treatment, as well nursing home and lunatic asylum.
[src:hospital/hospital] It typically treated the poor, as the rich would have been treated in their own homes.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals in this era were the first to require medical licenses for doctors, and compensation for negligence could be made.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hospitals were forbidden by law to turn away patients who were unable to pay.
[src:hospital/hospital] These hospitals were financially supported by waqfs, as well as state funds.
[src:hospital/hospital] In India, public hospitals existed at least since the reign of Firuz Shah Tughlaq in the 14th century.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Mughal emperor Jahangir in the 17th century established hospitals in large cities at government expense with records showing salaries and grants for medicine being paid for by the government.
[src:hospital/hospital] In China, during the Song dynasty, the state began to take on social welfare functions previously provided by Buddhist monasteries and instituted public hospitals, hospices and dispensaries.
[src:hospital/hospital] In Europe the medieval concept of Christian care evolved during the 16th and 17th centuries into a secular one.
[src:hospital/hospital] In 1682, Charles II founded the Royal Hospital Chelsea as a retirement home for old soldiers known as Chelsea Pensioners, an instance of the use of the word "hospital" to mean an almshouse.
[src:hospital/hospital] Ten years later, Mary II founded the Royal Hospital for Seamen, Greenwich, with the same purpose.
[src:hospital/hospital] The voluntary hospital movement began in the early 18th century, with hospitals being founded in London by the 1720s, including Westminster Hospital (1719) promoted by the private bank C.
[src:hospital/hospital] Hoare & Co and Guy's Hospital (1724) funded from the bequest of the wealthy merchant, Thomas Guy.
[src:hospital/hospital] Other hospitals sprang up in London and other British cities over the century, many paid for by private subscriptions.
[src:hospital/hospital] St Bartholomew's in London was rebuilt from 1730 to 1759, and the London Hospital, Whitechapel, opened in 1752.
[src:hospital/hospital] These hospitals represented a turning point in the function of the institution; they began to evolve from being basic places of care for the sick to becoming centers of medical innovation and discovery and the principal place for the education and training of prospective practitioners.
[src:hospital/hospital] Some of the era's greatest surgeons and doctors worked and passed on their knowledge at the hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] They also changed from being mere homes of refuge to being complex institutions for the provision and advancement of medicine and care for sick.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Charité was founded in Berlin in 1710 by King Frederick I of Prussia as a response to an outbreak of plague.
[src:hospital/hospital] When the Vienna General Hospital opened in 1784 as the world's largest hospital, physicians acquired a new facility that gradually developed into one of the most important research centers.
[src:hospital/hospital] Another Enlightenment era charitable innovation was the dispensary; these would issue the poor with medicines free of charge.
[src:hospital/hospital] The London Dispensary opened its doors in 1696 as the first such clinic in the British Empire.
[src:hospital/hospital] The idea was slow to catch on until the 1770s, when many such organisations began to appear, including the Public Dispensary of Edinburgh (1776), the Metropolitan Dispensary and Charitable Fund (1779) and the Finsbury Dispensary (1780).
[src:hospital/hospital] Dispensaries were also opened in New York 1771, Philadelphia 1786, and Boston 1796.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Royal Naval Hospital, Stonehouse, Plymouth, was a pioneer of hospital design in having "pavilions" to minimize the spread of infection.
[src:hospital/hospital] John Wesley visited in 1785, and commented "I never saw anything of the kind so complete; every part is so convenient, and so admirably neat.
[src:hospital/hospital] But there is nothing superfluous, and nothing purely ornamented, either within or without." This revolutionary design was made more widely known by John Howard, the philanthropist.
[src:hospital/hospital] In 1787 the French government sent two scholar administrators, Coulomb and Tenon, who had visited most of the hospitals in Europe.
[src:hospital/hospital] They were impressed and the "pavilion" design was copied in France and throughout Europe.
[src:hospital/hospital] English physician Thomas Percival (1740–1804) wrote a comprehensive system of medical conduct, *Medical Ethics; or, a Code of Institutes and Precepts, Adapted to the Professional Conduct of Physicians and Surgeons* (1803) that set the standard for many textbooks.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the mid-19th century, hospitals and the medical profession became more professionalised, with a reorganisation of hospital management along more bureaucratic and administrative lines.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Apothecaries Act 1815 made it compulsory for medical students to practise for at least half a year at a hospital as part of their training.
[src:hospital/hospital] Florence Nightingale pioneered the modern profession of nursing during the Crimean War when she set an example of compassion, commitment to patient care and diligent and thoughtful hospital administration.
[src:hospital/hospital] The first official nurses' training programme, the Nightingale School for Nurses, was opened in 1860, with the mission of training nurses to work in hospitals, to work with the poor and to teach.
[src:hospital/hospital] Nightingale was instrumental in reforming the nature of the hospital, by improving sanitation standards and changing the image of the hospital from a place the sick would go to die, to an institution devoted to recuperation and healing.
[src:hospital/hospital] She also emphasised the importance of statistical measurement for determining the success rate of a given intervention and pushed for administrative reform at hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] By the late 19th century, the modern hospital was beginning to take shape with a proliferation of a variety of public and private hospital systems.
[src:hospital/hospital] By the 1870s, hospitals had more than trebled their original average intake of 3,000 patients.
[src:hospital/hospital] In continental Europe the new hospitals generally were built and run from public funds.
[src:hospital/hospital] The National Health Service, the principal provider of health care in the United Kingdom, was founded in 1948.
[src:hospital/hospital] During the nineteenth century, the Second Viennese Medical School emerged with the contributions of physicians such as Carl Freiherr von Rokitansky, Josef Škoda, Ferdinand Ritter von Hebra, and Ignaz Philipp Semmelweis.
[src:hospital/hospital] Basic medical science expanded and specialisation advanced.
[src:hospital/hospital] Furthermore, the first dermatology, eye, as well as ear, nose, and throat clinics in the world were founded in Vienna, being considered as the birth of specialised medicine.
[src:hospital/hospital] By the late 19th and early 20th centuries, medical advancements such as anesthesia and sterile techniques that could make surgery less risky, and the availability of more advanced diagnostic devices such as X-rays, continued to make hospitals a more attractive option for treatment.
[src:hospital/hospital] Modern hospitals measure various efficiency metrics such as occupancy rates, the average length of stay, time to service, patient satisfaction, physician performance, patient readmission rate, inpatient mortality rate, and case mix index.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the United States, the number of hospitalizations grew to its peak in 1981 with 171 admissions per 1,000 Americans and 6,933 hospitals.
[src:hospital/hospital] This trend subsequently reversed, with the rate of hospitalization falling by more than 10% and the number of US hospitals shrinking from 6,933 in 1981 to 5,534 in 2016.
[src:hospital/hospital] Occupancy rates also dropped from 77% in 1980 to 60% in 2013.
[src:hospital/hospital] Among the reasons for this are the increasing availability of more complex care elsewhere such as at home or the physicians' offices and also the less therapeutic and more life-threatening image of the hospitals in the eyes of the public.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the US, a patient may sleep in a hospital bed, but be considered outpatient and "under observation" if not formally admitted.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the U.S., inpatient stays are covered under Medicare Part A, but a hospital might keep a patient under observation which is only covered under Medicare Part B, and subjects the patient to additional coinsurance costs.
[src:hospital/hospital] In 2013, the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) introduced a "two-midnight" rule for inpatient admissions, intended to reduce an increasing number of long-term "observation" stays being used for reimbursement.
[src:hospital/hospital] In 2016 and 2017, healthcare reform and a continued decline in admissions resulted in US hospital-based healthcare systems performing poorly financially.
[src:hospital/hospital] Microhospitals, with bed capacities of between eight and fifty, are expanding in the United States.
[src:hospital/hospital] Similarly, freestanding emergency rooms, which transfer patients that require inpatient care to hospitals, were popularised in the 1970s and have since expanded rapidly across the United States.
[src:hospital/hospital] The Catholic Church is the largest non-government provider of health care services in the world.
[src:hospital/hospital] It has around 18,000 clinics, 16,000 homes for the elderly and those with special needs, and 5,500 hospitals, with 65 percent of them located in developing countries.
[src:hospital/hospital] In 2010, the Church's Pontifical Council for the Pastoral Care of Health Care Workers said that the Church manages 26% of the world's health care facilities.
[src:hospital/hospital] Modern hospitals derive funding from a variety of sources.
[src:hospital/hospital] They may be funded by private payment and health insurance or public expenditure, charitable donations.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the United Kingdom, the National Health Service delivers health care to legal residents funded by the state "free at the point of delivery", and emergency care free to anyone regardless of nationality or status.
[src:hospital/hospital] Due to the need for hospitals to prioritise their limited resources, there is a tendency in countries with such systems for 'waiting lists' for non-crucial treatment, so those who can afford it may take out private health care to access treatment more quickly.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the United States, hospitals typically operate privately and in some cases on a for-profit basis, such as HCA Healthcare.
[src:hospital/hospital] The list of procedures and their prices are billed with a chargemaster; however, these prices may be lower for health care obtained within healthcare networks.
[src:hospital/hospital] Legislation requires hospitals to provide care to patients in life-threatening emergency situations regardless of the patient's ability to pay.
[src:hospital/hospital] Privately funded hospitals which admit uninsured patients in emergency situations incur direct financial losses, such as in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:hospital/hospital] As the quality of health care has increasingly become an issue around the world, hospitals have increasingly had to pay serious attention to this matter.
[src:hospital/hospital] Independent external assessment of quality is one of the most powerful ways to assess this aspect of health care, and hospital accreditation is one means by which this is achieved.
[src:hospital/hospital] In England, hospitals are monitored by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:hospital/hospital] The World Health Organization reported in 2011 that being admitted to a hospital was far riskier than flying.
[src:hospital/hospital] Globally, the chance of a patient being subject to a treatment error in a hospital was about 10%, and the chance of death resulting from an error was about one in 300.
[src:hospital/hospital] 7% of hospitalised patients in developed countries, and 10% in developing countries, acquire at least one health care-associated infection.
[src:hospital/hospital] In the U.S., 1.7 million infections are acquired in hospital each year, leading to 100,000 deaths, figures much worse than in Europe where there were 4.5 million infections and 37,000 deaths.
[src:hospital/hospital] Modern hospital buildings are designed to minimise the effort of medical personnel and the possibility of contamination while maximising the efficiency of the whole system.
[src:hospital/hospital] Travel time for personnel within the hospital and the transportation of patients between units is facilitated and minimised.
[src:hospital/hospital] The building also should be built to accommodate heavy departments such as radiology and operating rooms while space for special wiring, plumbing, and waste disposal must be allowed for in the design.
[src:hospital/hospital] However, many hospitals, even those considered "modern", are the product of continual and often badly managed growth over decades or even centuries, with utilitarian new sections added on as needs and finances dictate.
[src:hospital/hospital] Some newer hospitals now try to re-establish design that takes the patient's psychological needs into account, such as providing more fresh air, better views and more pleasant colour schemes.
[src:hospital/hospital] These ideas harken back to the late eighteenth century, when the concept of providing fresh air and access to the 'healing powers of nature' were first employed by hospital architects in improving their buildings.
[src:hospital/hospital] The research of British Medical Association is showing that good hospital design can reduce patient's recovery time.
[src:hospital/hospital] Exposure to daylight is effective in reducing depression.
[src:hospital/hospital] Single-sex accommodation help ensure that patients are treated in privacy and with dignity.
[src:hospital/hospital] Exposure to nature and hospital gardens is also important – looking out windows improves patients' moods and reduces blood pressure and stress level.
[src:hospital/hospital] Open windows in patient rooms have also demonstrated some evidence of beneficial outcomes by improving airflow and increased microbial diversity.
[src:hospital/hospital] Eliminating long corridors can reduce nurses' fatigue and stress.
[src:hospital/hospital] Another ongoing major development is the change from a ward-based system (where patients are accommodated in communal rooms, separated by movable partitions) to one in which they are accommodated in individual rooms.
[src:hospital/hospital] The ward-based system has been described as very efficient, especially for the medical staff, but is considered to be more stressful for patients and detrimental to their privacy.
[src:hospital/hospital] A major constraint on providing all patients with their own rooms is however found in the higher cost of building and operating such a hospital; this causes some hospitals to charge for private rooms.
